WEBVTT

00:06.381 --> 00:08.383
[tense music playing]

00:35.744 --> 00:40.707
[man 1] Everything for his future
depended on this special.

00:43.793 --> 00:46.421
Elvis was at the low point of his career,

00:46.504 --> 00:49.215
doing movies he didn't wanna do.

00:52.510 --> 00:55.638
He hadn't been onstage in seven years.

00:55.722 --> 00:59.559
[man 2] You all know what we're here for,
right? The Elvis Presley Special.

01:01.186 --> 01:05.774
[man 1] The '68 Comeback Special
would let him know

01:05.857 --> 01:09.611
if there was still an audience
for him as a performer.

01:09.694 --> 01:11.696
[tense music continues]

01:13.990 --> 01:18.870
[Schilling] If Elvis did not give
the greatest performance of his career,

01:19.496 --> 01:20.789
it was the end.

01:21.790 --> 01:25.043
[man 3] When Elvis
first came on the scene,

01:25.126 --> 01:27.087
it was a revelation.

01:27.170 --> 01:29.714
[cheering and screaming]

01:31.382 --> 01:32.550
[camera shutter clicking]

01:32.634 --> 01:37.597
The way he looked in the early days,
it was as cool as it possibly gets.

01:42.727 --> 01:45.188
But it evolved to a thing in the '60s.

01:45.271 --> 01:49.359
He was doing music that wasn't as great
as the music he did in the very beginning.

01:49.442 --> 01:52.570
He was doing movies
that nobody believed in.

01:52.654 --> 01:54.614
I'll buy you the biggest steak
you ever had.

01:54.697 --> 01:55.865
[barking]

01:55.949 --> 01:58.493
[Robertson] He was walking a fine line

01:58.576 --> 02:00.912
between, "I'm the real thing,"

02:01.621 --> 02:03.665
or, "I've lost it."

02:06.751 --> 02:11.214
We are now gonna see
whether he's really back or not.

02:11.297 --> 02:13.758
We're gonna see really what he's made of.

02:13.842 --> 02:14.843
[music fades out]

02:18.930 --> 02:21.474
[man 4] Just before they come onstage,

02:21.558 --> 02:24.727
Elvis calls the director
into the dressing room

02:24.811 --> 02:27.438
and said, "I can't go out there.
I can't do it."

02:28.648 --> 02:30.275
And the audience were coming in.

02:32.026 --> 02:32.986
Glenn?

02:34.154 --> 02:35.155
Go?

02:35.238 --> 02:38.158
Okay. Now, y'all know
what we're here for, right?

02:38.241 --> 02:40.702
And the director says, "Look, Elvis."

02:41.536 --> 02:44.289
"You've got to go out there."
Elvis is in the leather jacket.

02:44.372 --> 02:46.374
[somber music playing]

02:47.917 --> 02:50.420
[Luhrmann] And the director says,
"I'll tell you what."

02:50.503 --> 02:52.046
"You go out there,

02:52.130 --> 02:55.049
and if you don't like it,
I'll pretend the tapes were destroyed."

02:55.133 --> 02:57.135
And he makes him this crazy promise.

02:59.012 --> 03:00.555
And so, Elvis goes out.

03:01.181 --> 03:03.183
[fans cheering in distance]

03:05.268 --> 03:07.312
[woman] He was definitely aware
of the stakes, yes.

03:09.022 --> 03:11.482
[announcer in distance]
And here's Elvis Presley!

03:11.566 --> 03:14.360
And he knew that this could be a failure
and that would be it.

03:14.444 --> 03:17.530
It could ruin his career.
And he was very aware of that.

03:18.615 --> 03:22.994
[man 2] Uh, welcome to NBC
and the Elvis Presley Special.

03:23.077 --> 03:25.121
[audience applauding]

03:27.999 --> 03:30.084
You can do better.
I'm gonna say it all over again.

03:30.168 --> 03:31.794
I wanna really hear something.

03:31.878 --> 03:35.006
Welcome to NBC
and the Elvis Presley Special!

03:35.089 --> 03:38.301
-[audience cheering loudly]
-[drummer drumming]

03:42.805 --> 03:45.642
And here's Elvis Presley.

03:45.725 --> 03:47.727
[women screaming]

03:47.810 --> 03:49.812
[band playing rock 'n' roll tune]

04:04.327 --> 04:05.995
[music stops]

04:06.079 --> 04:07.914
Well, I'm gonna
have to do it sooner or later,

04:07.997 --> 04:10.708
so I might as well get on with it, baby.
Let's go.

04:10.792 --> 04:12.877
[opening of "Heartbreak Hotel" playing]

04:22.220 --> 04:24.555
Better get on with it again.
I missed it that time.

04:24.639 --> 04:26.140
[audience laughing]

04:26.224 --> 04:29.644
Elvis kind of fumbles the first entry.
And they have to start again.

04:30.144 --> 04:33.439
And he's really nervous.
He's sweating nerves.

04:33.523 --> 04:35.066
[scattered applause]

04:36.234 --> 04:38.486
-[director] Okay, we're ready.
-My boy, my boy.

04:39.487 --> 04:41.572
They're gonna put me away for a while.

04:42.824 --> 04:45.243
[man 5] It's just hard to remember
when you see him

04:45.326 --> 04:48.037
that once he had been the King.

04:48.121 --> 04:50.623
[Elvis] How long am I gonna be
standing here? Are we ready?

04:51.624 --> 04:55.003
It's getting embarrassing standing
out here, Steve. I gotta do something.

04:56.129 --> 04:58.548
[Thompson] It's shocking,
because he's very nervous.

04:58.631 --> 05:01.009
He's so visibly insecure.

05:02.343 --> 05:05.305
So overwhelmed by the size of the moment.

05:06.097 --> 05:09.309
-[Steve] Okay, are you ready?
-[Elvis] No, but we'll try anyway.

05:09.392 --> 05:12.270
[Thompson] Whoever this person was
standing on this stage

05:12.353 --> 05:16.482
was a shell of the rock star
who just a decade earlier

05:16.566 --> 05:19.444
terrified all of mainstream America.

05:19.527 --> 05:21.487
[drum beat hammering]

05:23.865 --> 05:25.867
[bass line playing]

05:25.950 --> 05:27.827
["My Baby Left Me" playing]

05:29.037 --> 05:33.624
♪ Yes, my baby left me
Never said a word ♪

05:34.417 --> 05:36.753
[Elvis] We got a seven-year contract
with Paramount Pictures.

05:37.503 --> 05:40.340
And overnight, it was all gone.
It was like a dream.

05:42.342 --> 05:43.885
[reporter] Say something to your fans.

05:43.968 --> 05:46.971
Do you have any particular message
you'd like to pass on to them?

05:51.059 --> 05:52.935
[Elvis] And so, I became

05:53.644 --> 05:54.896
very discouraged.

05:54.979 --> 05:56.481
[song continues]

06:02.653 --> 06:03.905
[song ends]

06:03.988 --> 06:05.615
[man] And here is Elvis Presley!

06:05.698 --> 06:07.700
[audience cheering]

06:12.538 --> 06:14.040
[cheering fades out]

06:14.123 --> 06:17.210
[host] Just a few weeks ago,
a young man from Memphis, Tennessee,

06:17.293 --> 06:19.253
recorded a song on the Sun label.

06:19.337 --> 06:23.716
He's only 19 years old.
Elvis Presley, let's give him a nice hand.

06:23.800 --> 06:25.802
[audience applauding]

06:25.885 --> 06:27.887
["That's All Right" playing]

06:28.888 --> 06:31.349
♪ Well, that's all right, Mama ♪

06:31.432 --> 06:33.142
♪ That's all right for you ♪

06:33.726 --> 06:35.520
♪ That's all right, Mama ♪

06:35.603 --> 06:38.398
♪ Just anyway you do
That's all right ♪

06:38.481 --> 06:40.274
[Elvis] I've always liked music.

06:40.358 --> 06:42.235
My mother and dad both loved to sing.

06:43.277 --> 06:45.154
They'd tell me
that when I was 3 or 4 years old,

06:45.238 --> 06:47.782
I got away from them in church
and walked up in front of the choir

06:47.865 --> 06:49.283
and started beating time.

06:49.784 --> 06:53.121
You have to remember, back in those days,
music is very segregated.

06:53.204 --> 06:55.665
Most music that we heard was all Black.

06:55.748 --> 06:57.125
And it was rhythm and blues,

06:57.208 --> 06:59.293
B.B. King, Little Richard.

06:59.377 --> 07:03.589
White people was playing Pat Boone,
the McGuire Sisters… [chuckling]

07:03.673 --> 07:06.467
…and we really wasn't interested
in that kind of music.

07:07.635 --> 07:13.683
[Thompson] America was deeply scared
of Black culture infecting

07:14.434 --> 07:15.393
white children.

07:17.103 --> 07:22.108
And here comes Elvis,
who took the music and the moves

07:22.191 --> 07:27.238
that he saw in the juke joints of
the Mississippi and Memphis of his youth,

07:28.030 --> 07:31.075
the music he grew up loving,
and put that onstage.

07:33.369 --> 07:38.124
[Schilling] This gave us our own music
that was not our parents' music.

07:38.207 --> 07:42.170
It was dangerous music,
'cause it was not our society's music,

07:42.253 --> 07:44.130
especially down South.

07:44.213 --> 07:45.923
That was just taboo.

07:46.007 --> 07:49.510
Elvis mostly back then
did covers of Black artists.

07:49.594 --> 07:51.345
["That's All Right"
by Arthur Crudup playing]

07:51.429 --> 07:52.847
♪ Yeah, now that's all right, Mama ♪

07:52.930 --> 07:54.599
♪ That's all right for you ♪

07:54.682 --> 08:00.438
[Love] Elvis was from the Deep South,
so he wanted to be around Black people.

08:01.147 --> 08:05.193
I asked him, "How did you come about
really loving Black people's music?"

08:06.652 --> 08:09.655
He said he would go around
to Black churches

08:09.739 --> 08:13.034
and just stand at the windows
and listen to their music.

08:13.659 --> 08:16.204
[congregation singing indistinctly]

08:16.287 --> 08:18.623
[Robertson] He was a prime example

08:18.706 --> 08:21.292
of showing what happens

08:21.375 --> 08:25.755
when you put together
music coming down from the mountains

08:25.838 --> 08:28.841
and music coming up the Mississippi River,

08:28.925 --> 08:30.551
and where that meets.

08:30.635 --> 08:33.888
And they explode,
and that became rock and roll.

08:33.971 --> 08:37.141
[Big Joe Turner singing]
♪ I said, "Shake, rattle and roll" ♪

08:37.225 --> 08:41.562
[Love] Nobody white was singing like that,
or wasn't even acting like that onstage.

08:41.646 --> 08:43.773
[Elvis] ♪ I said
"Shake, rattle and roll" ♪

08:43.856 --> 08:46.984
[Love] We thought it was funny
because we would say things like,

08:47.068 --> 08:49.779
"Oh, he's just trying
to be Black." [laughs]

08:49.862 --> 08:52.532
But he really wasn't.
That was just how he was.

08:53.115 --> 08:56.410
That was the controversy
that everybody was having at that time.

08:56.494 --> 08:59.956
'Cause his fans
didn't want him to be Black,

09:00.540 --> 09:04.210
and I don't even think they realized
that's the kind of singing he was doing.

09:04.293 --> 09:07.713
But we, as Black artists
and Black singers,

09:07.797 --> 09:10.800
we could tell the difference between Elvis

09:10.883 --> 09:13.928
and the other white singers
that were coming along at that time.

09:15.179 --> 09:19.350
The world was trying to fight us
not to do that, to keep separated.

09:19.433 --> 09:23.813
But music is not gonna separate you.
Music is going to bring you together.

09:25.231 --> 09:27.692
[Thompson] Elvis was an ambitious artist.

09:29.110 --> 09:32.363
He was also a child
who grew up in poverty,

09:32.446 --> 09:35.908
whose greatest fear was being poor again.

09:35.992 --> 09:40.621
His two greatest urges
are to make the most of his talent

09:41.247 --> 09:44.417
and to never ever be poor again.

09:44.500 --> 09:46.961
And those things
would fight each other his whole life.

09:47.044 --> 09:49.046
[contemplative music playing]

09:50.131 --> 09:52.967
[man 1] Most of Elvis Presley's
early music contemporaries

09:53.050 --> 09:56.304
are now merely footnotes
in the history of rock and roll.

09:56.387 --> 10:00.057
That's because they didn't have
the one thing that Elvis Presley had.

10:00.641 --> 10:04.687
Colonel Tom Parker,
the shrewdest manager in the business.

10:06.606 --> 10:08.441
[Thompson] When the Colonel
looked at Elvis,

10:08.524 --> 10:12.528
he saw a big, shiny idol
that America would worship.

10:13.237 --> 10:17.033
And when Elvis looked in the mirror,
he saw B.B. King.

10:17.742 --> 10:22.413
Those two versions
of the same person could never coexist,

10:22.496 --> 10:25.041
and the Colonel's Elvis

10:26.250 --> 10:27.585
killed the other Elvis.

10:28.628 --> 10:32.089
[man 2] Elvis and the Colonel
started working together in 1955

10:32.173 --> 10:37.428
when Elvis was out on the road
doing tours promoting his Sun singles,

10:37.511 --> 10:40.181
and the Colonel was managing Hank Snow.

10:40.848 --> 10:43.726
And basically, they got on
the same package tour together,

10:43.809 --> 10:45.603
and the Colonel was able to see

10:46.145 --> 10:48.731
what Elvis was about,
and the audience reaction,

10:48.814 --> 10:50.941
and how talented he really was.

10:51.942 --> 10:53.444
Almost immediately, he starts

10:53.527 --> 10:59.033
to maneuver of how he's going to
take over the management of Elvis.

11:00.451 --> 11:02.703
[Thompson] Colonel Parker
came up as a carnival barker.

11:02.787 --> 11:04.497
He thought Elvis was merch.

11:04.580 --> 11:07.416
He thought Elvis was a widget
he could sell to America.

11:07.500 --> 11:09.502
[contemplative music continues]

11:10.127 --> 11:13.297
[Luhrmann] In Elvis's mind,
the Colonel was some kind of genius.

11:14.924 --> 11:17.134
He was a kind of genius of selling.

11:17.218 --> 11:21.555
He was a genius showman,
he was a genius carny, really.

11:22.473 --> 11:26.435
And he had absolutely brilliant
entertainment ideas.

11:28.854 --> 11:32.733
[Schilling] When Colonel met with Elvis
and talked to him about

11:32.817 --> 11:35.736
TV exposure, about film,

11:35.820 --> 11:38.155
that's how the Colonel took over.

11:38.239 --> 11:39.907
Elvis wasn't 21 yet.

11:40.574 --> 11:44.370
[Elvis] I wasn't known at all until
Col. Parker started managing me, you see.

11:44.453 --> 11:47.790
And then I got on television,
and then I started being known.

11:47.873 --> 11:49.750
Elvis Presley, and here he is.

11:49.834 --> 11:52.503
-[band playing exciting tune]
-[audience applauding]

11:53.421 --> 11:55.047
[strums guitar]

11:55.131 --> 11:58.467
♪ Well, get out of that kitchen
And rattle those pots and pans ♪

12:00.261 --> 12:02.972
♪ Get out of that kitchen
And rattle those pots and pans ♪

12:04.348 --> 12:05.891
♪ Well, roll my breakfast… ♪

12:05.975 --> 12:09.270
[Springsteen] Colonel is summed up
in one sentence.

12:09.353 --> 12:13.274
"Last year, my boy had
a million dollars' worth of talent."

12:13.357 --> 12:16.485
"This year, he has a million dollars."

12:17.236 --> 12:20.072
[laughing] That's Colonel Tom Parker
in a nutshell.

12:20.906 --> 12:23.701
[Luhrmann] He kind of invented
the merch we know today.

12:23.784 --> 12:26.203
It was the Colonel's idea
to put Elvis's face on everything.

12:26.287 --> 12:30.374
The only kind of merch that really existed
up till then was sort of for Mickey Mouse.

12:30.458 --> 12:32.209
He just took it to another level.

12:32.960 --> 12:37.006
[Parker] No one can deny that this artist,
whether they like it or not,

12:37.089 --> 12:39.759
has a tremendous amount
of energy and talent.

12:39.842 --> 12:44.430
The name Elvis Presley is becoming
a household word one way or the other.

12:45.890 --> 12:48.893
[Springsteen] The night Elvis appeared
on The Ed Sullivan Show,

12:48.976 --> 12:51.228
I knew I was seeing something

12:51.312 --> 12:54.231
that possibly hadn't been seen before,

12:54.315 --> 12:56.984
which was a new type of human being.

12:57.067 --> 12:58.652
A 20th century man.

12:59.904 --> 13:02.656
-[audience applauding]
-[women screaming excitedly]

13:03.616 --> 13:07.203
I was a child,
and I was excited by the music.

13:08.454 --> 13:11.332
-♪ Ready, set, go, man, go ♪
-[drum beating in time to lyrics]

13:11.415 --> 13:13.292
♪ I got a gal that I love so ♪

13:13.375 --> 13:15.085
-[rest of band joins in]
-♪ I'm ready ♪

13:15.169 --> 13:17.421
♪ Ready, ready, ready, I'm ready ♪

13:17.505 --> 13:19.840
♪ Ready, ready, ready, I'm ready ♪

13:19.924 --> 13:23.552
♪ Ready, ready, ready
I'm ready, ready, ready to rock and roll ♪

13:23.636 --> 13:26.430
[Springsteen] It struck me deeply
even at that young age,

13:26.514 --> 13:30.351
the open sexuality of his appearance,

13:30.434 --> 13:33.103
the way he combed his hair,
or the makeup he put…

13:33.187 --> 13:36.273
He wore makeup, you know, in 1956.

13:36.357 --> 13:37.817
♪ Ready, ready to rock and roll ♪

13:37.900 --> 13:40.402
♪ Now, the flat-top cats
And the dungaree dolls ♪

13:40.486 --> 13:42.947
♪ Are headed to the gym
To the sock-hop ball ♪

13:43.030 --> 13:45.324
♪The joint is really jumping
The cats are going wild ♪

13:45.407 --> 13:48.077
♪ The music really sends me
I dig that crazy style ♪

13:50.538 --> 13:53.123
[Springsteen] And so the first thing I did
after I saw Elvis was

13:53.207 --> 13:56.502
got my mother,
we got to Mike Diehl's music shop.

13:56.585 --> 13:59.255
And I rented that guitar, came home,

13:59.338 --> 14:02.258
and I just smelled it,
touched it, and felt it.

14:02.341 --> 14:04.343
Made some noise on it. I couldn't play it.

14:05.386 --> 14:09.598
There were just all these things
that hadn't dawned on you before

14:09.682 --> 14:15.020
that he sort of opened the door for
and gave you an allowance to

14:15.604 --> 14:17.314
be who you actually are.

14:18.607 --> 14:20.776
You didn't have to follow the rules.

14:20.860 --> 14:22.987
[laughing] You could break the rules.

14:23.070 --> 14:24.321
♪ Rock and roll ♪

14:24.405 --> 14:27.074
-[guitar solo playing]
-[screaming continues]

14:35.875 --> 14:37.877
[rapid drumbeat plays]

14:39.128 --> 14:40.045
[man] I asked my mom.

14:40.629 --> 14:43.090
I said, "Do you remember
when Elvis Presley came on?"

14:43.173 --> 14:46.051
And she comes from
this very good Irish Catholic family.

14:46.135 --> 14:48.304
She said, "I thought it was disgusting."

14:49.054 --> 14:52.433
I was really disappointed.
I was like, "Mom, it's Elvis."

14:52.516 --> 14:54.143
"Well, I don't like it."

14:54.935 --> 14:58.355
His leg moving like that was not

14:59.148 --> 15:00.733
an affectation.

15:00.816 --> 15:03.485
That was not a cool stage move
he came up with.

15:03.569 --> 15:04.653
He couldn't help it.

15:04.737 --> 15:06.947
♪ Gonna rock and roll
Till the end of the night ♪

15:08.115 --> 15:10.409
♪ Ready, ready, ready, I'm ready ♪

15:10.492 --> 15:12.786
♪ Ready, ready, ready, I'm ready ♪

15:12.870 --> 15:14.038
♪ Ready, ready, ready ♪

15:14.121 --> 15:16.624
♪ I'm ready, ready, ready
To rock and roll ♪

15:16.707 --> 15:17.791
-Yeah.
-[music ends]

15:17.875 --> 15:19.293
[screaming continues]

15:20.085 --> 15:21.712
[Elvis] The first thing
people want to know

15:21.795 --> 15:23.881
is why I can't stand still
when I'm singing.

15:23.964 --> 15:25.758
I watch my audience and listen to them.

15:25.841 --> 15:28.385
And I know we're all
getting something out of our system.

15:28.469 --> 15:30.012
None of us knows what it is.

15:30.095 --> 15:33.307
The important thing is getting rid of it
and nobody's getting hurt.

15:34.350 --> 15:38.896
By the time he's on The Ed Sullivan Show
in September of '56,

15:38.979 --> 15:43.025
he's already been
on national television ten times and…

15:44.401 --> 15:48.822
And it's really the Milton Berle shows
that provide the controversy.

15:48.906 --> 15:49.865
["Hound Dog" playing]

15:49.949 --> 15:52.785
[preacher] My reasons on rock and roll
music and why I preach against it,

15:52.868 --> 15:54.244
I know what it does to you.

15:54.995 --> 15:59.625
And I know the evil… feeling
that you feel when you sing it.

15:59.708 --> 16:01.585
["Hound Dog" continues]

16:01.669 --> 16:04.046
[Elvis] I don't like to be called
"Elvis the Pelvis,"

16:04.129 --> 16:06.340
but it's one of the most
childish expressions

16:06.423 --> 16:09.343
I've ever heard coming
from an adult, "Elvis the Pelvis,"

16:09.426 --> 16:12.388
but if they wanna call me that,
there's nothing I can do about it,

16:12.471 --> 16:14.098
so I just have to accept it.

16:14.974 --> 16:17.810
[reporter] Now the chief reason
for all the criticism of Elvis Presley

16:17.893 --> 16:21.313
is that he's become
a sort of a sex symbol to teenage girls.

16:21.397 --> 16:23.148
They go wild over him.

16:23.232 --> 16:25.359
["Hound Dog" continues]

16:26.568 --> 16:31.448
His confidence, which is the fuel
of all of his sexual charisma,

16:31.532 --> 16:33.367
was the thing that scared America.

16:33.450 --> 16:35.244
♪ You ain't no friend of mine ♪

16:36.245 --> 16:37.746
[music ends]

16:37.830 --> 16:41.500
-♪ You ain't nothing but a hound dog ♪
-[music restarts]

16:41.583 --> 16:43.043
[all cheering excitedly]

16:43.127 --> 16:45.254
♪ Crying all the time ♪

16:46.797 --> 16:49.508
[man] One secret of Presley's popularity
with teenagers

16:49.591 --> 16:52.344
has been his lack of popularity
with their parents.

16:53.012 --> 16:56.432
So if parents quit criticizing
his singing, I predict

16:56.515 --> 16:59.018
Elvis Presley's star will fall

16:59.643 --> 17:01.645
as rapidly as it rose.

17:01.729 --> 17:02.730
Elvis was…

17:03.439 --> 17:05.566
was very unique because

17:05.649 --> 17:09.069
he wasn't a guy
that just hearing his music

17:09.153 --> 17:10.946
gave you the full picture.

17:11.030 --> 17:12.489
You had to see him.

17:12.573 --> 17:14.199
Elvis Presley!

17:14.283 --> 17:16.368
How about my boy? I love him.

17:16.452 --> 17:17.578
Wonderful. Hit it up.

17:17.661 --> 17:20.164
-♪ He ain't nothin' but a hound dog ♪
-[band starts playing]

17:20.247 --> 17:22.708
Hollywood was the ultimate destination
at that point

17:22.791 --> 17:24.626
if you wanted to be a famous person.

17:24.710 --> 17:28.047
It had worked for Frank Sinatra
and Bing Crosby and Dean Martin.

17:28.130 --> 17:31.091
So it was natural for them to look towards

17:31.842 --> 17:33.927
what… when is that going to happen?

17:34.011 --> 17:36.680
It wasn't if it was gonna happen,
but when it was gonna happen.

17:36.764 --> 17:38.724
Take your hand off my arm, Mr. Fields.

17:39.224 --> 17:41.643
How come you're so friendly
with the lady, boy?

17:41.727 --> 17:44.772
We met in Paris last year.
The King of France introduced us.

17:44.855 --> 17:47.524
[horn music playing]

17:47.608 --> 17:49.109
♪ If you're looking for trouble ♪

17:50.235 --> 17:52.071
♪ You came to the right place ♪

17:52.154 --> 17:54.907
[Luhrmann] Elvis was obsessed
with doing serious acting.

17:54.990 --> 17:57.910
He idolized James Dean,

17:57.993 --> 18:02.122
and he really wanted to be
like Dean and Brando,

18:02.206 --> 18:07.169
and, in fact, King Creole
was first offered to James Dean.

18:07.252 --> 18:09.379
And so, that's why he jumped at it.

18:09.463 --> 18:14.593
♪ My daddy was
A green-eyed mountain jack ♪

18:16.220 --> 18:18.806
[Springsteen] For my money,
Elvis is simply fun to watch.

18:18.889 --> 18:21.183
There were places for him to go in films.

18:21.266 --> 18:22.935
[intriguing music playing]

18:24.061 --> 18:26.105
[Elvis] I came to Hollywood
and I did four movies.

18:26.188 --> 18:29.483
So everything was happening,
really, in a short period of time.

18:34.571 --> 18:35.405
And then,

18:36.448 --> 18:38.575
right when I was going good,
I got drafted.

18:40.202 --> 18:42.871
And overnight, it was all gone.
It was like a dream.

18:42.955 --> 18:43.956
[snaps fingers] Pop.

18:47.417 --> 18:49.419
[music fades out]

18:50.170 --> 18:52.131
[man] I do solemnly swear…

18:52.214 --> 18:53.632
[men repeating]

18:53.715 --> 18:57.386
[man] …true faith and allegiance
to the United States of America.

18:57.469 --> 18:59.638
To the United States of America.

18:59.721 --> 19:03.058
[man] Congratulations, you are now
in the Army. You are all privates.

19:03.934 --> 19:05.394
[big band music playing]

19:05.477 --> 19:09.815
[reporter 1] His lucrative career as rock
and roll king interrupted for a while,

19:09.898 --> 19:14.611
Elvis Presley begins his military service
at Fort Chaffee, Arkansas.

19:14.695 --> 19:17.990
Uncle Sam doesn't play favorites,
and those celebrated sideburns,

19:18.073 --> 19:22.578
which were his trademark,
are sacrificed to military uniformity.

19:23.787 --> 19:24.872
[reporter 2] Elvis Presley,

19:24.955 --> 19:29.084
Private Elvis Presley
of the United States Army,

19:29.960 --> 19:33.505
is due to embark for Germany today.

19:36.717 --> 19:38.594
[tense music playing]

19:38.677 --> 19:41.096
[Schilling] He was
at the top of his career.

19:41.180 --> 19:43.807
The last thing he wanted to do
was go to the Army.

19:45.225 --> 19:46.310
It was a sad thing.

19:46.393 --> 19:50.063
I remember Elvis
as he's walking up on the ship

19:50.147 --> 19:52.107
with a duffel bag on his back

19:52.191 --> 19:56.111
and saying goodbye to all the fans
as he's going to Germany.

20:02.659 --> 20:04.536
Even though there wasn't a war,

20:05.454 --> 20:07.748
when you think of Germany
back in the '50s,

20:07.831 --> 20:09.958
that's like going to…

20:10.042 --> 20:11.919
[chuckles] …the worst place ever.

20:12.002 --> 20:14.296
[triumphant music playing]

20:15.631 --> 20:19.009
[reporter 3] This is the story of the role
played by the United States Army.

20:19.092 --> 20:24.556
Their job? Hold back the tide of Communism
in Germany and in free Europe.

20:24.640 --> 20:27.226
[Elvis] It's really
a privilege to be in Europe.

20:27.309 --> 20:30.020
It's something that I've looked forward to
for some time.

20:30.103 --> 20:33.023
I only regret that… uh…

20:33.899 --> 20:35.817
I can't do some…

20:36.902 --> 20:39.404
some shows and different things
while I'm here,

20:39.488 --> 20:41.448
but I will be looking forward when my,

20:41.949 --> 20:44.034
uh, Army hitch is over,

20:44.117 --> 20:48.997
I would like very much to come back
on a regular tour of Europe.

20:49.081 --> 20:50.832
[reporter 4] Thank you very much,
Mr. Presley.

20:50.916 --> 20:52.834
And we wish you
a pleasant stay in Germany.

20:52.918 --> 20:54.169
[Elvis] Thank you very much.

20:56.255 --> 20:58.924
-Arrivederci. No, that's Italian.
-[people laughing]

20:59.424 --> 21:00.550
[chuckles]

21:00.634 --> 21:02.970
[Priscilla] I met Elvis in Germany.

21:03.053 --> 21:07.099
My father was in the Air Force,
and he was stationed over there.

21:07.182 --> 21:09.393
There was a place called the Eagles Club,

21:09.476 --> 21:13.647
and I was sitting at the Eagles Club
in the afternoon.

21:13.730 --> 21:16.400
There was a jukebox.
Back in the day, we played records.

21:16.984 --> 21:21.321
And I was writing to my friend
how much I hated it there,

21:21.405 --> 21:23.156
that I missed them all very much.

21:23.740 --> 21:26.743
And this guy came over to me,
introduced himself,

21:26.827 --> 21:28.662
and he said,
"Are you writing to your friends?"

21:28.745 --> 21:31.164
And I go, "Yeah, we just got here
three weeks ago."

21:33.041 --> 21:34.584
And he said, "Do you like Elvis?"

21:34.668 --> 21:37.254
And I said,
"Yeah, who doesn't like Elvis?"

21:37.337 --> 21:39.089
He said, "Would you like to meet him?"

21:39.172 --> 21:41.174
[gentle piano music playing]

21:42.175 --> 21:45.846
[Priscilla] At home, I told my father,
"Dad, I met somebody at the Eagles Club,

21:45.929 --> 21:48.515
and he wanted to know
if I wanted to meet Elvis."

21:48.598 --> 21:50.767
Well, that didn't go well at all,

21:50.851 --> 21:54.438
'cause my father wasn't really a fan,
and neither was my mother.

21:56.565 --> 21:58.900
And I only thought it was a one-time shot,

21:58.984 --> 22:01.945
never ever thinking
that I would be asked to go back.

22:03.238 --> 22:05.407
We went over that weekend on a Saturday.

22:06.742 --> 22:08.910
There was a glass on top of the piano,

22:08.994 --> 22:12.622
and as he's singing, he's really
rocking it like Jerry Lee Lewis did.

22:13.123 --> 22:14.791
I'm looking at it going, "Oh my God."

22:14.875 --> 22:16.501
"It's gonna splash. It's gonna fall."

22:16.585 --> 22:18.378
And just as it started to fall,

22:18.462 --> 22:21.465
he picked it up and looked over
to everybody like it was a trick.

22:24.426 --> 22:27.596
Being in the Army was so not his thing.
It was very foreign.

22:27.679 --> 22:31.016
And he's alone,
and usually he has people around him.

22:31.099 --> 22:34.644
He has his guys around him,
even before he went into the Army.

22:34.728 --> 22:37.147
So he was alone,
really, for the first time.

22:37.981 --> 22:41.234
It sounded like to me
that he needed someone to talk to,

22:41.318 --> 22:44.112
and Elvis would really
pour his heart out to me.

22:44.196 --> 22:45.530
He'd just lost his mother.

22:48.784 --> 22:50.619
[Elvis] It wasn't only
like losing a mother.

22:50.702 --> 22:54.873
It was like losing a friend,
a companion, someone to talk to.

22:54.956 --> 22:58.877
I could wake her up any hour of the night,
if I was worried about something.

22:58.960 --> 23:00.545
She'd get up, try to help me.

23:02.506 --> 23:07.636
[Jackson] Elvis and Gladys's relationship
was very close from the very beginning.

23:07.719 --> 23:11.932
They lived in
an incredibly poor area of Tupelo.

23:12.015 --> 23:14.309
She was always trying
to make their life better.

23:14.393 --> 23:16.395
And also, at the same time,

23:16.478 --> 23:20.065
Vernon ends up getting sent
to jail for forging a check.

23:20.607 --> 23:23.652
So for a lot of the time
that Elvis was a kid,

23:23.735 --> 23:27.239
it was just he and Gladys,
and Gladys worked very hard to

23:27.322 --> 23:29.533
feed him, clothe him, get him into school.

23:29.616 --> 23:31.368
[gentle piano music continues]

23:31.451 --> 23:34.621
She was his support mechanism
for the pressure,

23:34.704 --> 23:37.416
the stress, everything
that was going on with the career.

23:37.499 --> 23:38.959
[melancholy music playing]

23:39.793 --> 23:43.755
[Priscilla] I had compassion
and felt horrible for him.

23:43.839 --> 23:46.967
Understanding, you know,
being away especially,

23:47.050 --> 23:50.053
losing a mom that he was so close to.

23:50.137 --> 23:52.139
So that's kind of how we connected.

23:54.766 --> 23:57.686
And he was very nervous
about whether or not

23:57.769 --> 24:01.731
he would still be in the business
or still even sing again.

24:05.902 --> 24:08.280
He was away for quite a while,

24:08.363 --> 24:11.700
and he thought a lot of his fans
would forget him.

24:11.783 --> 24:13.869
Someone else would be coming in,
someone new.

24:13.952 --> 24:16.746
-[hopeful string music playing]
-[reporter] Say something to your fans.

24:16.830 --> 24:20.250
Do you have any particular message
that you'd like to pass on to them?

24:21.168 --> 24:23.837
[Elvis] Yes, I would. I'd like to say that

24:23.920 --> 24:28.425
in spite of the fact that I'll be
out of their eyes for some time,

24:28.508 --> 24:30.177
I hope I'm not out of their minds.

24:31.553 --> 24:33.597
And I'll be looking forward to the time

24:33.680 --> 24:36.766
when I can come back
and entertain again like I did.

24:38.560 --> 24:39.561
[Luhrmann] Elvis,

24:40.645 --> 24:43.315
he was deeply sensitive
and deeply insecure.

24:45.150 --> 24:48.487
Like that little boy who was ashamed
of what happened to his dad,

24:48.570 --> 24:50.197
who was ashamed of their poverty,

24:50.280 --> 24:53.074
ashamed of what happened to his mom,
was trying to mend things

24:53.158 --> 24:56.870
and make things good
and always wanted to please people.

24:56.953 --> 24:59.080
I mean, he was a profound pleaser,

24:59.164 --> 25:01.750
and that made him so charismatic onstage,

25:01.833 --> 25:04.044
but also gave him an Achilles' heel.

25:04.127 --> 25:06.463
And that is that you want love. Mass love.

25:06.546 --> 25:07.923
But the more mass love you get,

25:08.006 --> 25:10.050
the bigger the hole gets,
the more you need.

25:11.510 --> 25:12.636
When he was in the Army,

25:12.719 --> 25:16.014
I think that's when
it really starts to wear away at him,

25:16.097 --> 25:19.434
not having the love of the audience.

25:20.310 --> 25:22.020
[music fades out]

25:22.103 --> 25:23.271
[faint gunshots]

25:23.355 --> 25:26.608
[Schilling] Normally,
when an artist was big,

25:26.691 --> 25:30.946
and they went to the Army and was out of
the sight of everybody for a couple years,

25:31.029 --> 25:33.573
they never were able
to pick their career back up.

25:34.157 --> 25:35.909
Elvis was never out of sight.

25:35.992 --> 25:37.994
["(Now and Then There's) A Fool Such as I"
playing]

25:41.081 --> 25:43.750
[Jackson] The most important thing
that the Colonel does

25:43.833 --> 25:46.336
before Elvis goes into the Army,

25:46.419 --> 25:50.298
is he gets him to record
a bunch of material.

25:51.132 --> 25:55.804
♪ Pardon me if I'm sentimental ♪

25:55.887 --> 25:58.139
♪ When we say goodbye ♪

25:58.848 --> 26:01.518
♪ Don't be angry with me ♪

26:01.601 --> 26:03.979
[Jackson] They have huge hits
while Elvis is in Germany.

26:04.062 --> 26:07.816
So if you weren't really
paying attention to the national news

26:07.899 --> 26:10.986
and what Elvis
was actually physically doing,

26:11.069 --> 26:13.029
you'd think he was still making records.

26:14.197 --> 26:19.160
♪ Now and then, there's a fool such as I ♪

26:19.244 --> 26:21.079
[Schilling] Before he went to Germany,

26:21.162 --> 26:22.956
he was still

26:23.039 --> 26:23.915
the rebel.

26:23.999 --> 26:27.586
♪ As a fool, such as I am ♪

26:27.669 --> 26:30.297
[Schilling] And here he was,
a foot soldier,

26:30.380 --> 26:33.425
staying up all night on patrols.

26:34.843 --> 26:37.137
Getting frostbite in the snow.

26:37.220 --> 26:41.057
♪ I'm a fool, but I'll love you, dear ♪

26:41.141 --> 26:42.475
[man] Colonel wrote him letters,

26:42.559 --> 26:45.895
again and again, explaining
what he'd done to promote his records.

26:45.979 --> 26:49.316
♪ As a fool, such as I ♪

26:49.399 --> 26:52.986
[backup singers] ♪ Fool such as I ♪

26:54.237 --> 26:57.991
Telling him that he'd made a new deal,
that there was a movie to come out and do…

26:58.074 --> 27:00.702
Telling him, "I made another deal
for another two movies."

27:03.455 --> 27:05.957
[Elvis] I would like to say
that when I get out of the Army…

27:06.041 --> 27:06.916
[music ends]

27:07.000 --> 27:09.002
…I'm looking forward to…

27:09.085 --> 27:13.256
to just picking up where I left off
when I came into the service.

27:14.299 --> 27:16.885
["Stuck on You" by Elvis Presley playing]

27:16.968 --> 27:20.180
[reporter] And I take it from that
that you really enjoy what you're doing,

27:20.263 --> 27:22.349
or what you were doing
before you went into service.

27:22.432 --> 27:24.017
[Elvis] Oh yes, I do.

27:24.100 --> 27:27.520
In fact, that was the hardest part
of the entire military service.

27:27.604 --> 27:29.147
It was being away from it.

27:29.230 --> 27:30.774
[reporter] Being away from the fans?

27:30.857 --> 27:32.942
Just being away
from show business altogether.

27:33.026 --> 27:34.861
That was the hardest part of all.

27:35.528 --> 27:39.074
Kept thinking about the past all the time,
contemplating the future.

27:39.157 --> 27:42.327
♪ Stick because I'm stuck on you… ♪

27:43.078 --> 27:44.663
[Springsteen] There was no rock musician

27:44.746 --> 27:49.334
who had an established
20, 30-year career that you could look to.

27:50.085 --> 27:52.087
That person didn't exist.

27:53.088 --> 27:56.383
Everybody's idea of success was Sinatra.

27:56.466 --> 27:59.344
Sinatra had the incredible career.

27:59.427 --> 28:01.971
And those types of entertainers, you know?

28:02.055 --> 28:04.766
That was sort of… That was the peak.

28:04.849 --> 28:06.393
[audience applauding]

28:06.476 --> 28:10.689
[announcer] The Frank Sinatra Timex Show,
"Welcome Home, Elvis."

28:11.940 --> 28:12.774
There he is!

28:12.857 --> 28:14.776
[O'Brien] The thing that stands out to me,

28:15.276 --> 28:17.654
which is a very crafty move,

28:17.737 --> 28:22.075
is he's welcomed home
in a big special by Frank Sinatra.

28:23.034 --> 28:25.412
[Sinatra] Well, Elvis,
that's our little "welcome home" gift.

28:25.495 --> 28:27.372
The two years you lost while in the Army.

28:27.455 --> 28:29.958
And looking back over it,
I'm stuck with the realization

28:30.041 --> 28:32.252
that maybe you didn't miss
so much after all.

28:32.752 --> 28:35.922
As a matter of fact, all you seemed
to have lost is your sideburns.

28:36.840 --> 28:40.635
Now, folks, what would you say
if I were gonna sing another song now?

28:40.719 --> 28:45.140
It's a very clear moment

28:45.223 --> 28:49.018
where Elvis is accepted into the club.

28:49.769 --> 28:53.815
Frank is telling the country,
"He's a good kid."

28:53.898 --> 28:56.860
"He served his country,
went in the Army. He's back now."

28:57.569 --> 29:00.238
But at the same time,
Elvis is giving something up.

29:01.197 --> 29:03.408
Because in order to get into the club,

29:03.491 --> 29:07.412
you also have to give up,
"This person's dangerous."

29:07.495 --> 29:08.913
"This person's a threat."

29:08.997 --> 29:11.666
"My daughter might run off with this guy."

29:11.750 --> 29:14.335
That's over. It's almost like
a negotiated settlement.

29:16.004 --> 29:18.506
Frank Sinatra, they call him
the chairman of the board

29:18.590 --> 29:20.592
because he runs show business.

29:20.675 --> 29:23.636
He is perceived as the guy

29:23.720 --> 29:26.765
who can bless certain people,

29:26.848 --> 29:30.727
and, "Look, we're together
singing each other's songs."

29:30.810 --> 29:34.856
♪ For, my darling ♪

29:34.939 --> 29:38.443
♪ I love you ♪

29:38.526 --> 29:40.612
-Man, that's pretty.
-[audience laughing]

29:40.695 --> 29:46.868
♪ And I always will ♪

29:47.786 --> 29:49.120
[audience cheering]

29:49.204 --> 29:52.373
[reporter] Elvis, some radio stations
are cutting off rock and roll.

29:52.999 --> 29:54.292
What's your comment on that,

29:54.375 --> 29:57.337
and what will happen to your career
if rock and roll died out?

29:57.837 --> 30:01.466
If rock and roll
died completely out, well,

30:02.217 --> 30:03.968
then I'd have to do something else

30:04.052 --> 30:05.845
in the line of music. Maybe…

30:06.638 --> 30:07.472
uh…

30:08.556 --> 30:09.933
opera. [laughs]

30:10.016 --> 30:11.267
I don't know, really.

30:11.351 --> 30:13.019
[classical piano playing]

30:13.770 --> 30:16.397
[Luhrmann] Elvis, when he was in the Army,

30:16.481 --> 30:20.401
he was exposed to a lot of European music,
and he particularly loved Mario Lanza.

30:20.485 --> 30:22.278
And Mario Lanza was an opera singer.

30:22.362 --> 30:25.406
And I think that's where
this cross-fertilization happens.

30:25.490 --> 30:30.578
[Lanza singing opera music in Italian]

30:45.093 --> 30:48.596
[opera music transitions to rock guitar]

30:48.680 --> 30:50.515
["Surrender" by Elvis Presley playing]

30:50.598 --> 30:54.519
♪ When we kiss, my heart's on fire ♪

30:54.602 --> 30:57.355
[Luhrmann] Elvis changed his musical style
and his voice.

30:57.438 --> 30:59.649
The way he spoke changed very much.

30:59.732 --> 31:01.359
Elvis becomes really

31:02.068 --> 31:06.406
serious after the Army
with big vocal singing.

31:07.156 --> 31:10.743
[Jackson] He can get almost into
that sort of operatic range.

31:11.703 --> 31:13.955
So as soon as he's back from the Army,

31:14.038 --> 31:17.000
the Colonel gets him
right into the studio again.

31:17.083 --> 31:20.962
They're recording stuff
that is much more adult-leaning.

31:21.045 --> 31:23.423
♪ Of our love and all its glory ♪

31:23.506 --> 31:27.844
[Corgan] The thing about Elvis as
an artist is he had hits in every genre.

31:28.553 --> 31:32.056
Does he sound like Elvis in every song?
Yeah. How do you do that?

31:32.557 --> 31:34.392
It's not like he changed himself.

31:34.475 --> 31:37.437
He makes those genres bend to him,
not the other way around.

31:37.520 --> 31:41.190
♪ Won't you please surrender to me ♪

31:41.274 --> 31:44.402
It's the pure arc light of his talent.

31:44.485 --> 31:47.155
♪ Your lips, your arms, your heart, dear ♪

31:47.238 --> 31:49.407
[backup singers] ♪ Surrender ♪

31:49.490 --> 31:54.579
[Elvis] ♪ Be mine forever ♪

31:55.371 --> 32:01.586
♪ Be mine tonight ♪

32:03.922 --> 32:06.341
Elvis comes back
and he performs a benefit show.

32:06.424 --> 32:10.261
This is a Pearl Harbor
charity organization.

32:11.512 --> 32:14.349
[announcer] Look out, here he comes!
Ladies and gentlemen,

32:14.432 --> 32:17.602
it looks as if… it's Elvis Presley!

32:17.685 --> 32:19.020
[all screaming]

32:19.103 --> 32:20.897
["Heartbreak Hotel" playing]

32:20.980 --> 32:23.942
♪ Well, since my baby left me ♪

32:24.025 --> 32:26.611
-[fans continue screaming]
-♪ I found a new place to dwell ♪

32:26.694 --> 32:31.532
♪ Down at the end of Lonely Street
At Heartbreak Hotel ♪

32:31.616 --> 32:36.245
♪ Where I'll be so lonely, baby ♪

32:36.329 --> 32:38.915
♪ I'll be lonely ♪

32:38.998 --> 32:42.335
♪ You'll be so lonely, you could die ♪

32:43.586 --> 32:48.007
He gets on that stage, and he is just

32:48.091 --> 32:49.717
charisma personified.

32:49.801 --> 32:53.137
-[guitar solo playing]
-[fans screaming]

32:56.724 --> 32:59.310
[Thompson] It was the peak of something.

32:59.978 --> 33:02.772
And you would think
that this would be the relaunch.

33:03.272 --> 33:05.692
And instead, it was the end of something.

33:06.567 --> 33:08.569
[drum flourish playing]

33:13.992 --> 33:15.368
[Thompson] He walks off that stage,

33:15.451 --> 33:18.621
and he wouldn't walk
on another stage for seven more years.

33:18.705 --> 33:20.873
[contemplative music playing]

33:20.957 --> 33:23.376
You don't think rock and roll
is dying then, huh?

33:23.459 --> 33:27.380
In 1956, when I first started out,
I was hearing the same thing.

33:27.463 --> 33:29.590
That rock and roll is dead, is dying out.

33:30.091 --> 33:33.678
I'm not saying it won't die out,
because it may be dead tomorrow.

33:33.761 --> 33:34.721
I don't know.

33:35.221 --> 33:36.305
I wish I did know.

33:37.849 --> 33:41.185
[Priscilla] Elvis kept calling me
periodically out of the blue.

33:41.269 --> 33:46.649
He felt safe talking to me
and expressing to me his fears.

33:46.733 --> 33:48.276
His likes, his dislikes.

33:48.359 --> 33:52.071
I didn't have any media attention,
and this is when I was dating him.

33:54.115 --> 33:55.867
He would tell me about Colonel Parker,

33:55.950 --> 33:58.870
and he really depended on Colonel Parker

33:58.953 --> 34:01.831
to take care of him
and get him into movies.

34:02.832 --> 34:05.543
And he was hoping for bigger opportunities

34:05.626 --> 34:08.463
to be able to be in the type of films
that he wanted to be in.

34:09.172 --> 34:13.593
More serious, something good
that he felt he was connected to.

34:15.636 --> 34:20.349
After the Army, Elvis did a couple
of non-singing movies, and nobody went.

34:20.433 --> 34:23.394
[announcer] Elvis Presley
in his most dramatic role,

34:23.478 --> 34:25.897
as the half-breed in Flaming Star.

34:25.980 --> 34:29.942
Torn between two loves, two loyalties,
and fighting to save them both.

34:30.026 --> 34:32.820
Flaming Star, dramatic dynamite.

34:32.904 --> 34:34.322
[woman] It was a good film.

34:34.405 --> 34:38.576
A very good film, but he didn't sing.
He didn't get the girl.

34:39.077 --> 34:42.955
And he died, so you can imagine
how that went over with his fans.

34:43.039 --> 34:44.916
They hated it, you know?

34:44.999 --> 34:47.043
White men let her die!

34:47.126 --> 34:49.712
[Luhrmann] And the Colonel
kind of used that to say,

34:49.796 --> 34:51.506
"Let's surround you with a lot of girls,

34:51.589 --> 34:54.425
put you in really cool clothes,
you sing a lot of songs,

34:54.509 --> 34:56.135
and keep the plot light and fluffy,

34:56.219 --> 34:58.513
so as many people as possible
can buy a ticket."

34:59.180 --> 35:01.474
"You're gonna make a river of money."
And they did.

35:01.557 --> 35:03.142
["Can't Help Falling in Love" playing]

35:03.226 --> 35:06.771
[Luhrmann] And I think that is
the beginning of his corruption.

35:06.854 --> 35:11.692
♪ Wise men say ♪

35:12.902 --> 35:18.282
♪ Only fools rush in… ♪

35:18.366 --> 35:20.326
And that's when he had
that five-year contract

35:20.409 --> 35:21.953
that had basically musicals.

35:22.036 --> 35:28.167
♪ I can't help falling in love… ♪

35:28.251 --> 35:30.586
That's what people wanted to see him sing.

35:32.213 --> 35:34.298
[Parker] We're heading back to Hollywood,

35:34.382 --> 35:36.676
to start the picture
Thursday at Paramount.

35:36.759 --> 35:38.928
-[Elvis] Thursday at Paramount.
-[Parker] For Hal Wallis.

35:39.011 --> 35:40.221
Two or three of them this year.

35:40.304 --> 35:41.931
[reporter] You're gonna be that busy?

35:42.014 --> 35:44.225
["Rock-A-Hula Baby" playing]

35:44.308 --> 35:46.894
♪ The way she moves her hips
To her fingertips ♪

35:46.978 --> 35:49.313
♪ I feel I'm heaven bound ♪

35:49.397 --> 35:51.524
[Thompson] They put out Blue Hawaii.

35:51.607 --> 35:54.110
The movie's an unbelievable
box office hit.

35:54.193 --> 35:55.695
But something else happens

35:55.778 --> 35:58.698
that is very beneficial
to Elvis's bank account

35:58.781 --> 36:02.368
and ultimately almost lethal
to his creative life,

36:02.451 --> 36:06.247
which is the soundtrack
spends 20 weeks at number one.

36:06.330 --> 36:09.959
It's a huge hit, and say what you
want to say about Colonel Parker,

36:10.042 --> 36:12.086
but the guy is a brilliant businessman.

36:12.170 --> 36:13.796
And he immediately realized,

36:13.880 --> 36:18.593
"If we put out movies
where Elvis sings to young women

36:18.676 --> 36:20.595
who aren't wearing a whole lot of clothes,

36:20.678 --> 36:22.805
and we put out a companion soundtrack,

36:22.889 --> 36:24.932
the things will promote each other."

36:25.892 --> 36:27.977
And so, that was now the formula.

36:28.060 --> 36:30.062
Oh, it's a beach party. Come on.

36:30.813 --> 36:34.066
And they just did it
over and over and over again.

36:34.150 --> 36:36.027
[twangy guitar playing]

36:36.110 --> 36:37.528
[bongo tune playing]

36:37.612 --> 36:42.241
And like every drug,
the high is a little less every time.

36:42.325 --> 36:44.493
[performing "Do the Clam"]
♪ Everybody gather round ♪

36:44.577 --> 36:45.786
[bongo rhythm playing]

36:45.870 --> 36:48.206
♪ Listen to that bongo sound ♪

36:48.289 --> 36:49.749
From a business perspective,

36:49.832 --> 36:52.084
which is the only thing
the Colonel is interested in,

36:52.168 --> 36:53.878
the movies are terrible,

36:53.961 --> 36:58.132
but the business of Elvis
is actually as good as it's ever been.

36:58.216 --> 37:01.135
♪ Do the clam, do the clam ♪

37:02.220 --> 37:04.639
♪ Grab your barefoot baby by the hand... ♪

37:04.722 --> 37:07.433
[Jackson] He became more and more
plastic-looking in those movies.

37:07.516 --> 37:09.894
I'm sorry, buddy.
I can't be in both places at once.

37:09.977 --> 37:12.480
[O'Brien] Elvis's hair in those movies,
at a certain point,

37:12.563 --> 37:15.274
it's like a cotton candy
that they spray-painted black

37:15.358 --> 37:16.859
and then they varnished it.

37:16.943 --> 37:19.111
They brushed it with some yak butter.

37:19.195 --> 37:22.406
He's not real.
He's not a real person anymore.

37:22.490 --> 37:25.159
The backgrounds behind him aren't real.

37:25.243 --> 37:26.202
Nothing's real.

37:26.285 --> 37:29.247
["Do the Clam" continues]

37:30.039 --> 37:31.749
[Thompson] Colonel Parker's
plan is working.

37:31.832 --> 37:33.793
He made more than Steve McQueen.

37:33.876 --> 37:35.753
He made more than Gregory Peck.

37:35.836 --> 37:37.546
He made more than Cary Grant.

37:37.630 --> 37:41.342
He was the highest-paid
movie star in America.

37:41.425 --> 37:43.344
They would pay astronomically.

37:43.427 --> 37:45.429
But what the Colonel realized was

37:45.513 --> 37:49.016
the more money you could get out of them,
the cheaper he could make the films.

37:49.100 --> 37:52.061
["Do the Clam" continues]

38:03.489 --> 38:06.826
[Elvis] And I was doing
a lot of pictures close together,

38:07.326 --> 38:09.078
and the pictures got very similar.

38:09.870 --> 38:12.331
I'd read the first
four or five pages of it, and I knew

38:12.415 --> 38:17.086
that it was just a different name
with 12 new songs in it.

38:17.169 --> 38:19.422
The songs were mediocre in most cases.

38:19.505 --> 38:21.549
They even stopped writing new music.

38:21.632 --> 38:23.676
They'd just sort of regurgitate old songs,

38:24.260 --> 38:26.387
throw a sort of plotline together.

38:26.470 --> 38:28.889
[Thompson] He's putting together
these grab-bag records

38:28.973 --> 38:30.641
of songs that no one else wanted

38:30.725 --> 38:33.102
because the requirement
to be on an Elvis song

38:33.185 --> 38:34.979
was Colonel Parker got the publishing.

38:35.855 --> 38:38.316
These were all naked money grabs.

38:38.399 --> 38:39.650
They had this one record,

38:39.734 --> 38:44.155
there is Elvis posing with the RCA dog

38:44.238 --> 38:47.950
who is sitting on top
of a cash register. It's insane.

38:48.034 --> 38:51.370
♪ Dig right in and do the clam ♪

38:51.454 --> 38:54.957
-[all cheering]
-[music fades out]

38:55.041 --> 38:57.752
The scripts get worse,
the songs get worse.

38:57.835 --> 39:01.589
Until, eventually, Elvis Presley
is making movies in three weeks

39:01.672 --> 39:03.382
where there's one take of everything

39:03.466 --> 39:05.634
and he's singing
"Old MacDonald Has a Farm."

39:05.718 --> 39:07.595
[upbeat music playing]

39:08.346 --> 39:09.305
♪ Old MacDonald… ♪

39:09.388 --> 39:10.639
-[chuckles]
-Oh boy.

39:10.723 --> 39:12.516
♪ Ee-i-ee-i-o ♪

39:12.600 --> 39:17.146
♪ And on that farm he had some chicks
Ee-i-ee-i-o ♪

39:17.229 --> 39:19.774
♪ With a cluck-cluck here
A cluck-cluck there ♪

39:19.857 --> 39:21.942
-Embarrassing.
-Yeah.

39:22.026 --> 39:25.446
♪ And when those chicks got out of line
Chicken fricassee ♪

39:25.946 --> 39:28.115
-[Priscilla] That, to me, is a crime.
-[Schilling] Yeah.

39:28.199 --> 39:29.575
-It is a crime.
-Yeah.

39:29.658 --> 39:32.870
To put him
in that situation and sing that song.

39:34.163 --> 39:36.374
That makes him a laughingstock,
and he knew it.

39:36.457 --> 39:37.416
[Schilling] Yeah.

39:37.500 --> 39:38.918
-Yeah.
-He knew it.

39:40.127 --> 39:42.129
[melancholy music playing]

39:43.923 --> 39:46.300
[man] When did you permanently
move in to Graceland?

39:46.884 --> 39:49.637
That was in 1963.

39:56.143 --> 39:57.728
I know he'd be very angry.

39:57.812 --> 40:00.856
I saw him throw
so many scripts across the room.

40:00.940 --> 40:03.025
Frustration, anger.

40:03.901 --> 40:05.027
Um…

40:05.945 --> 40:09.156
Lost a little bit
on where his career was going.

40:09.240 --> 40:11.951
Because those were not the roles
that he wanted.

40:12.868 --> 40:16.122
[Elvis] Uh, Hollywood's image of me
was wrong, and I knew it.

40:16.205 --> 40:17.998
And I couldn't do anything about it.

40:19.291 --> 40:23.254
I didn't know what to do. I just felt
I was obligated to things that I didn't

40:24.130 --> 40:25.381
fully believe in.

40:25.464 --> 40:28.008
At a certain stage, I had no say-so in it.

40:29.718 --> 40:32.555
I didn't have
final approval of the script.

40:33.597 --> 40:36.600
Which means that I couldn't say,

40:36.684 --> 40:38.394
"This is not good for me."

40:39.353 --> 40:41.313
And so, I became

40:42.148 --> 40:43.315
very discouraged.

40:43.941 --> 40:46.235
They couldn't have paid me
no amount of money in the world

40:46.318 --> 40:49.447
to make me feel any satisfaction inside.

40:51.574 --> 40:55.870
The first time I heard him say no

40:56.704 --> 41:01.208
was we were here in Bel Air,

41:01.292 --> 41:03.127
and he looks at this script,

41:03.878 --> 41:06.630
and he throws it against the wall.

41:06.714 --> 41:09.216
"I'm not doing another one of these."

41:10.634 --> 41:12.136
Within a few hours,

41:12.219 --> 41:14.263
there was the record company,

41:15.347 --> 41:17.016
there was William Morris,

41:18.726 --> 41:20.352
there was the studio,

41:20.436 --> 41:22.188
and there was Colonel Parker.

41:23.439 --> 41:27.985
And, "If you don't do these contracts,

41:28.819 --> 41:30.821
you won't do anything."

41:30.905 --> 41:32.907
[melancholy music continues]

41:33.741 --> 41:35.159
[Priscilla] He really had no choice.

41:36.035 --> 41:36.952
Not really.

41:37.036 --> 41:39.038
He had to fulfill the contract.

41:40.581 --> 41:42.791
You could even see it physically.

41:43.876 --> 41:47.171
[Elvis] I cared so much,
until I became physically ill.

41:47.254 --> 41:49.215
I would become violently ill.

41:55.471 --> 41:59.767
No matter how big Elvis got,
he's still the guy that grew up

42:00.518 --> 42:02.102
in a tar shack.

42:06.232 --> 42:07.858
There's always somebody
in your ear saying,

42:07.942 --> 42:10.486
"Know what?
You're not far from going back there."

42:13.656 --> 42:16.867
If Elvis cared so much about money,
why did he blow it the way he did?

42:16.951 --> 42:19.245
Nobody blew money like Elvis.
He was legendary.

42:20.788 --> 42:22.164
This wasn't about money.

42:24.458 --> 42:27.086
The quotient is not money

42:27.169 --> 42:29.672
versus the thing you want to get to.

42:29.755 --> 42:32.258
The quotient is, "You'll be abandoned."

42:33.717 --> 42:37.012
Money is just some form of testament
that people care.

42:37.680 --> 42:40.683
It's the abandonment thing
that they use against you.

42:40.766 --> 42:46.480
[Luhrmann] The Colonel had immense ability
to tap into Elvis's insecurity

42:47.064 --> 42:49.775
and really infantilize him.

42:52.736 --> 42:54.280
He always felt

42:54.363 --> 42:59.702
that he owed the Colonel his career,
and I think it was very hard for him

42:59.785 --> 43:03.330
to say, "I wanna stand alone here."

43:03.414 --> 43:05.457
"I'm making my own decisions."

43:05.541 --> 43:07.960
[Springsteen] Elvis's closest collaborator

43:08.836 --> 43:11.672
was somebody who didn't understand him.

43:12.923 --> 43:15.676
That was the tragedy
of their relationship.

43:16.468 --> 43:20.306
There was nobody to tell Elvis
actually how good he was, you know?

43:20.389 --> 43:23.183
In a deep… In a deep enough way.

43:24.393 --> 43:25.978
[melancholy music continues]

43:27.771 --> 43:29.982
I mean, you think about having
all of that talent

43:30.065 --> 43:33.193
and being that revolutionary an artist.

43:33.986 --> 43:37.489
And to have a world
that doesn't really understand you,

43:37.573 --> 43:40.326
that basically thinks
you're kind of a clown.

43:43.746 --> 43:47.666
[O'Brien] If you look at Elvis's career
through much of the '60s,

43:48.500 --> 43:52.129
you're looking at an artist
who's completely isolated

43:52.963 --> 43:54.673
from anything that fed him.

43:54.757 --> 43:56.175
This is a guy who…

43:57.509 --> 44:00.554
was born performing in front of people.

44:00.638 --> 44:01.764
Now he's isolated.

44:07.853 --> 44:10.481
[Thompson] Elvis had been dangerous enough

44:10.564 --> 44:13.067
to recognize danger when he saw it.

44:14.026 --> 44:15.819
He saw the Rolling Stones.

44:16.445 --> 44:17.780
He saw the Beatles.

44:18.739 --> 44:21.533
He knew how they were making America feel

44:21.617 --> 44:23.911
because he had made America feel that way.

44:23.994 --> 44:26.914
["I Want to Hold your Hand"
by The Beatles playing]

44:29.458 --> 44:30.668
[fans screaming]

44:30.751 --> 44:34.755
♪ Oh yeah, I'll tell you somethin' ♪

44:35.547 --> 44:38.050
♪ I think you'll understand ♪

44:38.133 --> 44:40.928
♪ When I say that somethin' ♪

44:41.011 --> 44:44.264
[reporter] One psychiatrist recently said
you're nothing but four Elvis Presleys.

44:44.348 --> 44:46.350
It's not true. It's not true.

44:46.433 --> 44:47.267
[all laughing]

44:47.351 --> 44:48.769
♪ I want to hold your hand ♪

44:49.520 --> 44:51.647
[reporter 2] On every sign,
there is hero worship

44:51.730 --> 44:54.525
that recalls the heydays
of Elvis Presley and Frank Sinatra.

44:55.234 --> 44:58.737
[O'Brien] In '64,
there's just this huge tidal wave.

44:58.821 --> 45:02.241
Everything changes.
The hair changes, the clothes change.

45:02.324 --> 45:05.619
Overnight, the Beatles
make everybody irrelevant,

45:05.703 --> 45:07.454
and then everyone has to catch up.

45:07.538 --> 45:11.250
♪ Let me hold your hand ♪

45:11.333 --> 45:13.711
♪ I want to hold your hand ♪

45:14.795 --> 45:17.798
Oh my gosh,
I was listening to the Beatles too.

45:17.881 --> 45:22.177
You know, I was listening to Mick Jagger.
I mean, he came on like Elvis did.

45:22.261 --> 45:25.180
He was out jumping all over the place.
I'm like, "What the heck?"

45:27.182 --> 45:28.684
The music was changing.

45:28.767 --> 45:34.106
♪ I can't hide, I can't hide ♪

45:36.442 --> 45:40.612
[Priscilla] The Beatles came to our house
in Bel Air, which was a funny evening.

45:40.696 --> 45:44.491
-♪ I want to hold your hand ♪
-[music ends]

45:45.534 --> 45:48.245
[Priscilla] When they did come in,
they were so nervous.

45:48.328 --> 45:50.289
In fact, Elvis sat down on the couch,

45:50.873 --> 45:53.959
John Lennon and Paul McCartney
just stared at him.

45:54.752 --> 45:58.380
Never said a word. Just looked at him.
They were so nervous.

45:58.464 --> 46:01.550
And Elvis basically was saying,
"Well, if you're not gonna talk…"

46:01.633 --> 46:03.719
He turned on the TV. [laughs]

46:03.802 --> 46:06.096
They were just mesmerized by him.

46:06.180 --> 46:07.848
[gentle music playing]

46:07.931 --> 46:09.600
[Schilling] I remember seeing them,

46:09.683 --> 46:12.436
and we start talking, and John said,

46:12.519 --> 46:16.023
"I didn't have the courage
to tell Elvis this,

46:16.106 --> 46:17.357
but would you tell him?"

46:17.441 --> 46:20.444
He said, "You see these sideburns?"
and I said, "Yeah."

46:20.527 --> 46:22.863
He said, "I almost got
kicked out of high school

46:22.946 --> 46:25.365
because I wanted to look like Elvis."

46:25.449 --> 46:28.911
"And we wouldn't be here today
if it wasn't for him."

46:30.621 --> 46:34.458
The Beatles were the writers
of their songs at the time,

46:34.541 --> 46:36.835
and before the Beatles, in general,

46:36.919 --> 46:40.380
songwriters wrote the songs,
singers sang the songs.

46:40.464 --> 46:43.592
That's what took it to the next level,

46:43.675 --> 46:46.094
the fact that the Beatles wrote.

46:46.178 --> 46:51.016
And that's what gave us,
the youth at that time, a voice.

46:52.935 --> 46:55.062
[Corgan] Of course,
the Beatles worshiped Elvis,

46:55.145 --> 46:57.856
but they weren't necessarily
listening to his new records.

46:58.482 --> 47:00.275
[Luhrmann] He was the original rebel.

47:00.776 --> 47:03.529
He was the original conduit

47:03.612 --> 47:07.115
to make rock and roll
hugely popular with youth.

47:08.075 --> 47:10.994
And now, he's relegated
to really being a family entertainer.

47:11.078 --> 47:13.205
And I think that really hurt.

47:13.789 --> 47:15.874
[Elvis] I've never written a song.
I wish I could.

47:15.958 --> 47:18.502
I wish I was like some of my, uh, rivals,

47:18.585 --> 47:21.296
'cause they're pretty good songwriters.
But me, I…

47:21.380 --> 47:24.007
I did good to get out of high school,
you know? [laughs]

47:24.842 --> 47:27.594
[O'Brien] Suddenly,
all these rock groups coming

47:27.678 --> 47:31.139
that are alluding to things
that are much deeper.

47:31.223 --> 47:35.727
Something that's about real life,
and that flips the script completely.

47:36.603 --> 47:39.982
[Luhrmann] There was
all of the mass racial tension,

47:40.065 --> 47:42.943
and then there was the economic tension,

47:43.026 --> 47:45.696
and then there was
what was going on in Vietnam,

47:45.779 --> 47:49.366
which is impossible to overstate
the impact on American culture of that.

47:50.033 --> 47:52.160
[reporter] The news tonight,
despite an official denial,

47:52.244 --> 47:55.414
is of a significant escalation
of the war in Vietnam.

47:55.497 --> 47:58.584
For the first time, American jets
have dumped tons of high explosives

47:58.667 --> 48:00.335
within the city limits of Haiphong.

48:00.419 --> 48:02.504
[O'Brien] No rock and roll performer
of the '50s

48:02.588 --> 48:04.965
was trying to get to something deeper.

48:05.048 --> 48:09.845
I think a big thing to me, is people
start looking for meaning in music.

48:09.928 --> 48:12.639
Real meaning, something that's deeper than

48:12.723 --> 48:15.642
anything they heard from Chuck Berry,

48:15.726 --> 48:17.644
anything they heard from Elvis.

48:18.228 --> 48:20.188
["Only a Pawn in Their Game"
by Bob Dylan playing]

48:20.272 --> 48:22.232
♪ A bullet from the back of a bush ♪

48:22.316 --> 48:24.401
♪ Took Medgar Evers' blood ♪

48:26.862 --> 48:30.616
♪ A finger fired the trigger to his name ♪

48:32.618 --> 48:36.705
♪ A handle hid out in the dark ♪

48:36.788 --> 48:39.291
♪ The hand set the spark ♪

48:39.374 --> 48:41.501
♪ Two eyes took the aim ♪

48:42.753 --> 48:45.005
♪ Behind a man's brain ♪

48:46.089 --> 48:48.216
♪ But he can't be blamed ♪

48:49.676 --> 48:54.097
♪ He's only a pawn in their game ♪

48:55.432 --> 48:57.142
[O'Brien] Suddenly, there's this

48:57.851 --> 48:58.852
poetry.

48:58.936 --> 49:04.358
♪ A South politician preaches
To the poor white man ♪

49:04.858 --> 49:09.237
There's poetry in music.
Folk music and then rock music.

49:10.906 --> 49:14.993
♪ "You're better than them
You been born with white skin" ♪

49:15.077 --> 49:19.873
The idea of Bob Dylan reciting
a type of poetry in his songs,

49:19.957 --> 49:23.126
it was like, "What's that?
Where does that come from?"

49:23.919 --> 49:29.007
People that were writing songs
really couldn't help but be a reflection

49:29.091 --> 49:30.884
of what was happening in the streets.

49:30.968 --> 49:37.099
♪ But it ain't him to blame
He's only a pawn in their game ♪

49:37.182 --> 49:39.935
[Corgan] Elvis didn't see himself
as a political figure.

49:40.727 --> 49:44.356
So it would have been probably weird
even from a "brand" point of view,

49:44.439 --> 49:46.566
especially when he's doing
big Hollywood movies.

49:46.650 --> 49:49.653
Like, is he gonna start jumping in
and doing topical songs?

49:49.736 --> 49:52.823
Elvis stayed on the sidelines
while the world was shifting towards

49:52.906 --> 49:56.284
a political, overt stance
with great intensity.

50:00.872 --> 50:04.126
[woman] Oh, Mr. Presley,
on the subject of the service,

50:04.209 --> 50:08.380
what is your opinion of war protesters?
And would you today refuse to be drafted?

50:09.339 --> 50:13.218
[Elvis] Honey, I'd just sooner keep my own
personal views about that to myself.

50:13.301 --> 50:16.680
'Cause I'm just an entertainer and I…
I'd rather not say.

50:16.763 --> 50:19.891
[woman] Do you think other entertainers
should keep their views to themselves too?

50:19.975 --> 50:22.102
[Elvis] No. I can't even say that.

50:24.062 --> 50:26.273
[Thompson] The only songs
Elvis could record at this point

50:26.356 --> 50:31.778
were songs that almost every other serious
recording artist in America had passed on.

50:31.862 --> 50:35.782
The greatest voice in America
was getting America's worst songs,

50:35.866 --> 50:38.535
and not only did no one stop him,

50:38.618 --> 50:41.204
no one in his camp
even seemed to understand

50:41.288 --> 50:43.540
that this was a problem, except for Elvis.

50:43.623 --> 50:46.793
I mean, Elvis might be lots of things,
but he's not an idiot.

50:46.877 --> 50:49.546
He can read a graph line
like anybody else.

50:49.629 --> 50:50.797
This is dying.

50:50.881 --> 50:52.049
I think he thought,

50:52.799 --> 50:56.219
"If this is ending, I want to end
as the Elvis I wanna be."

50:56.303 --> 50:57.888
"Not the Elvis they want me to be."

50:57.971 --> 51:00.974
["Run On" by Elvis Presley playing]

51:01.058 --> 51:02.768
[backup singers humming]

51:02.851 --> 51:05.937
[Elvis]
♪ Well, you may run on for a long time ♪

51:06.021 --> 51:08.440
[backup singers]
♪ Run along for a long time ♪

51:08.523 --> 51:10.525
[Elvis] ♪ Run on for a long time ♪

51:10.609 --> 51:13.153
♪ Let me tell you
God almighty gonna cut you down ♪

51:13.236 --> 51:17.157
♪ Go tell that long tongued liar
Go tell that midnight rider ♪

51:17.908 --> 51:21.036
♪ Tell the gambler, the rambler
The back-biter ♪

51:21.119 --> 51:22.454
[music fades out]

51:22.537 --> 51:25.040
[Jackson] How Great Thou Art
was an incredibly important

51:25.123 --> 51:26.374
milestone in his career

51:26.458 --> 51:30.921
because it showed him that
he could do what he wanted to do.

51:31.004 --> 51:32.672
And it necessarily didn't need to be

51:32.756 --> 51:35.383
the biggest commercial success
in the world,

51:35.467 --> 51:39.221
but that he could be in control
of his own destiny.

51:39.721 --> 51:41.681
♪ Great God almighty
Let me tell you what he said ♪

51:41.765 --> 51:43.558
♪ Go tell that long tongued liar ♪

51:43.642 --> 51:45.685
[Jackson] It's sort of
the first step towards,

51:45.769 --> 51:50.065
"I need to get back to who I am
as a person and as an artist."

51:50.732 --> 51:52.484
So, to go back to his gospel roots

51:52.567 --> 51:55.237
and sort of insist
that he make that record

51:55.320 --> 51:59.199
wasn't in line with what the Colonel
would have wanted him to do,

51:59.282 --> 52:01.201
which was just more pop music.

52:01.993 --> 52:05.038
[Love] I think if Elvis at that point
in his career

52:05.122 --> 52:07.082
wasn't able to do gospel music,

52:07.165 --> 52:09.501
I don't know what Elvis
would have been doing.

52:10.377 --> 52:12.337
So, he had to stand up.

52:12.420 --> 52:14.172
"This is what, really, I want to do."

52:14.256 --> 52:16.466
[reporter] Elvis,
is your first love Western music?

52:17.384 --> 52:19.052
[Elvis] No, sir, it's not.

52:19.136 --> 52:22.055
My first, I would say, would be, uh,

52:22.139 --> 52:23.557
spiritual music.

52:23.640 --> 52:27.435
I know practically every religious song
that's ever been written.

52:27.519 --> 52:30.063
["How Great Thou Art"
by Elvis Presley playing]

52:30.147 --> 52:32.107
[choir harmonizing]

52:32.190 --> 52:36.153
[Love] When he found out that I was
a gospel singer and I had gospel roots,

52:36.236 --> 52:39.447
I think that's what made me and him
really gravitate to one another,

52:39.531 --> 52:41.283
because that's how he wanted to sing.

52:41.366 --> 52:45.662
♪ Oh, Lord, my God ♪

52:45.745 --> 52:47.873
[Love] You're born with
certain feelings inside of you.

52:47.956 --> 52:50.250
And you can feel them
when you go different places.

52:50.333 --> 52:51.918
Like when I visit different churches,

52:52.002 --> 52:54.421
I can feel that spirit
that they have at that church.

52:55.589 --> 52:57.716
And Elvis wanted to feel that.

52:58.300 --> 53:03.471
♪ Then sings my soul ♪

53:04.848 --> 53:06.808
[Schilling] When I saw Elvis

53:06.892 --> 53:09.519
singing "How Great Thou Art"…

53:12.272 --> 53:14.983
it was the first time
I'd been to a recording session.

53:15.942 --> 53:20.071
I was sitting
right outside the glass window.

53:20.155 --> 53:24.784
I think he was really touched,
I mean, by something spiritual.

53:24.868 --> 53:27.204
Like his soul had left his body.

53:27.287 --> 53:32.167
♪ Then sings my soul ♪

53:33.710 --> 53:35.837
[Schilling] At the end of that session,

53:37.130 --> 53:39.549
he went down to his knees

53:39.633 --> 53:42.677
and he looked up and he had this little…

53:42.761 --> 53:45.972
He looked like a little boy,
proud smile on his face.

53:46.806 --> 53:48.975
He knew he had done something great.

53:49.059 --> 53:53.063
♪ How great ♪

53:53.146 --> 54:00.153
♪ Thou art ♪

54:00.237 --> 54:01.071
[music ends]

54:02.030 --> 54:05.575
He won three Grammys.

54:05.659 --> 54:09.287
And they were all for gospel music.
That tells you where his heart is.

54:09.371 --> 54:11.414
[gentle guitar music playing]

54:14.876 --> 54:19.256
If Elvis could have had a choice
of the music he would sing,

54:19.339 --> 54:20.966
it would be gospel,

54:21.049 --> 54:26.096
but he wasn't gonna make no money
and be no superstar as a gospel singer.

54:26.179 --> 54:29.099
So he had to take the route
that was going to, you know,

54:29.182 --> 54:32.102
get him very successful,
because, you know,

54:32.185 --> 54:34.980
the Colonel did not want him
to sing anymore.

54:35.063 --> 54:36.856
He just wanted him to stay in movies.

54:41.403 --> 54:44.656
That gospel album is the giveaway

54:44.739 --> 54:47.534
as to what was going on
in his internal life.

54:47.617 --> 54:50.203
["Thrill of Your Love"
by Elvis Presley playing]

54:50.287 --> 54:53.081
[Elvis] I wouldn't like
to stay in the same vein.

54:53.164 --> 54:56.960
I mean, I wouldn't like to be
at a standstill, you know what I mean?

54:57.043 --> 55:00.463
I'd like… I'd like to progress.

55:00.547 --> 55:02.924
I'd like to get married.
I'd like to have a family.

55:03.008 --> 55:05.719
It's definitely true.
It's a normal thing to do.

55:05.802 --> 55:08.388
Who wants to grow old and be alone?
You know what I mean?

55:08.471 --> 55:12.017
♪ Star above ♪

55:13.310 --> 55:15.854
[Priscilla] I was
in my dressing room at Graceland,

55:16.688 --> 55:20.150
and he said, "Cilla,"
and he knocked on my door,

55:20.233 --> 55:22.235
and he had something behind his back.

55:22.319 --> 55:24.904
♪ …to me ♪

55:24.988 --> 55:28.199
And then he said to me,
you know, "It's time."

55:28.783 --> 55:29.617
And he

55:30.201 --> 55:32.537
took a box out, and it was a wedding ring.

55:32.620 --> 55:34.956
♪ To the thrill… ♪

55:35.040 --> 55:36.249
[Priscilla] I was in shock.

55:36.333 --> 55:40.295
♪ Of your love ♪

55:40.378 --> 55:42.922
[Elvis] It's more important
to surround yourself with people

55:43.006 --> 55:46.259
who can give you a little happiness,
because you only pass through life once.

55:46.343 --> 55:47.969
You don't come back for an encore.

55:48.053 --> 55:51.973
Find that one girl, you know.
It's a thing that you can't rush.

55:54.184 --> 55:57.228
I'm thinking to myself,
"My dad's not gonna believe this."

55:57.312 --> 56:02.567
♪ Than to be all alone ♪

56:02.650 --> 56:04.986
I got pregnant the night we got married.
[laughs]

56:06.571 --> 56:10.158
And I'm like nervous, I'm going,
"Oh my God, I don't know if I…"

56:10.241 --> 56:13.495
"Am I ready to be a mother?" I was 21.

56:13.578 --> 56:17.832
I started crying one night. I've never
told this, but I started crying one night

56:17.916 --> 56:21.795
and he called me "Satnin" and he said,
"Satnin, what's the matter with you?"

56:21.878 --> 56:24.255
"What's the matter, baby?" You know? I go…

56:25.590 --> 56:26.591
"I'm scared."

56:26.674 --> 56:28.676
[heartfelt music playing]

56:31.638 --> 56:33.640
"I don't know if I'm ready for a baby."

56:33.723 --> 56:36.851
[Priscilla] And he goes, "You'll be
a great mother. You'll be a great mom."

56:37.352 --> 56:38.186
And I go,

56:38.853 --> 56:41.564
"I won't be able to do things
with you anymore."

56:41.648 --> 56:43.316
And he goes, "Yes, you will."

56:43.400 --> 56:46.778
I go, "You're not gonna want
babies around and kids around."

56:47.487 --> 56:50.073
We got married,
we're doing things together,

56:50.156 --> 56:51.449
we're going to Vegas.

56:52.742 --> 56:55.537
And I'm thinking,
"All that's gonna stop."

56:55.620 --> 56:58.206
My head is definitely different
than where his was going.

56:58.915 --> 57:00.959
And he is looking at being a dad.

57:02.836 --> 57:05.296
Elvis was definitely excited to be a dad.

57:06.005 --> 57:07.882
He was a little nervous, that's for sure.

57:08.758 --> 57:11.594
Didn't know how to hold a child,
or didn't think he did.

57:16.224 --> 57:18.101
And so, it turned out great.

57:23.773 --> 57:26.943
Eventually, he makes
the last movie for Paramount,

57:27.026 --> 57:29.487
Easy Come, Easy Go. It's a total flop.

57:29.571 --> 57:35.243
The record doesn't even chart
and sells just 30,000 copies.

57:37.120 --> 57:39.539
[Luhrmann] I don't think
he recognizes just

57:39.622 --> 57:43.543
how dire things are until one day
there's an actual headline

57:43.626 --> 57:46.463
in one of the trades, and it says,

57:47.046 --> 57:51.426
"There's no more appetite
for Presley films."

57:51.509 --> 57:53.511
[tense music playing]

57:57.307 --> 57:59.434
[Jorgensen] In the Colonel's mindset,
when you need to

57:59.517 --> 58:01.269
get people to focus again…

58:01.352 --> 58:04.856
In '56, he put him on
God knows how many TV shows.

58:04.939 --> 58:07.692
When he came back from the Army
and needed to reestablish…

58:07.775 --> 58:09.736
"I put him on the Frank Sinatra Show."

58:09.819 --> 58:11.196
Now he's got nothing.

58:11.279 --> 58:14.449
He says, "I need to go back
to my old trick, get him on TV."

58:15.742 --> 58:17.619
It was all or nothing.

58:22.665 --> 58:25.960
[Elvis] Years went by,
I really missed the audience contact.

58:26.044 --> 58:27.754
I really was getting bugged.

58:27.837 --> 58:31.466
I was doing so many movies,
and I couldn't really do what I could do.

58:31.549 --> 58:33.927
It all kept going,
and I really wanted to come back.

58:34.594 --> 58:38.223
The idea was, "It's time to have him
come back into everyone's living room."

58:38.306 --> 58:40.225
It only became

58:40.934 --> 58:44.395
what we know of now
as the '68 Comeback Special

58:44.479 --> 58:45.563
as it developed.

58:48.566 --> 58:50.443
[Priscilla] He didn't want
to be around people.

58:50.944 --> 58:54.656
He just wanted to relax,
go to the beach and just think.

58:57.617 --> 58:58.868
He was getting in shape.

59:00.495 --> 59:02.038
[Schilling] He started training.

59:02.121 --> 59:04.874
I think he must have lost 25 pounds.

59:06.209 --> 59:09.087
He was training like
this is the heavyweight championship.

59:10.129 --> 59:12.840
[Priscilla] I don't think
I've ever seen him

59:12.924 --> 59:15.301
that excited before.

59:16.928 --> 59:18.179
[man 1] Okay, here we go.

59:20.723 --> 59:22.350
[man 2] That's 512.

59:22.433 --> 59:25.728
[upbeat backing track playing]

59:25.812 --> 59:28.898
[Love] At that time, we didn't know
whether Elvis was gonna be there or not.

59:28.982 --> 59:31.985
Because a lot of times when you
do sessions, you're doing the band,

59:32.068 --> 59:33.736
then you're doing background singing

59:33.820 --> 59:36.948
and you're trying to get that
all together with the producers.

59:37.031 --> 59:39.492
And then Elvis popped up and he was there.

59:39.576 --> 59:40.785
[man 2] That's Take 501.

59:41.578 --> 59:43.830
["Saved" playing]
♪ I used to smoke ♪

59:43.913 --> 59:45.290
♪ I used to smoke ♪

59:45.373 --> 59:47.250
♪ Drink and dance the hoochie-coo ♪

59:47.333 --> 59:49.252
♪ I used to smoke and drink ♪

59:49.335 --> 59:51.754
♪ Smoke and drink
And dance the hoochie-coo ♪

59:51.838 --> 59:53.423
[Love] He sat and talked to us.

59:53.506 --> 59:55.508
"That sounds so good. How you guys doing?"

59:55.592 --> 59:57.969
Then he wanted to know who we were

59:58.052 --> 01:00:00.555
and what we were doing
and what kind of music we love.

01:00:00.638 --> 01:00:04.058
♪ That's why I'm saved
I am saved ♪

01:00:04.142 --> 01:00:07.061
[Love] He told us that he was nervous
about doing it, period.

01:00:07.145 --> 01:00:08.688
The whole '68 Special.

01:00:08.771 --> 01:00:11.691
He was nervous, 'cause
he hadn't done anything like that before.

01:00:11.774 --> 01:00:15.069
-[singing rock song]
-[music cuts out]

01:00:15.153 --> 01:00:16.112
Shit.

01:00:16.195 --> 01:00:19.824
People talk about the special now
based on what they remember,

01:00:19.907 --> 01:00:23.536
which is raw rock and roll Elvis returns.

01:00:23.620 --> 01:00:26.372
The Colonel tried
his very best to ruin that.

01:00:26.456 --> 01:00:28.374
["It Hurts Me" by Elvis Presley playing]

01:00:30.293 --> 01:00:33.212
♪ He never loved you ♪

01:00:35.048 --> 01:00:36.883
[Thompson] 'Cause
the special was full of skits,

01:00:36.966 --> 01:00:40.136
and he's fighting,
and there's silly little set pieces.

01:00:40.219 --> 01:00:43.556
♪ He'll never change ♪

01:00:45.767 --> 01:00:47.935
-[Elvis] Goddamn it.
-[man 1] Okay.

01:00:48.019 --> 01:00:49.729
[Thompson] Yes,
there's all this great music.

01:00:49.812 --> 01:00:51.731
There's also lots of

01:00:51.814 --> 01:00:53.983
Colonel Tom Parker crap all over it.

01:00:54.067 --> 01:00:55.568
[clacking]

01:00:55.652 --> 01:00:56.778
[man 2] Nine-oh-two.

01:00:57.362 --> 01:00:58.571
Five-ten.

01:00:59.197 --> 01:01:01.199
["Medley" by Elvis Presley playing]

01:01:05.495 --> 01:01:07.246
[starts singing, then stumbles]

01:01:07.330 --> 01:01:08.581
Goddamn it.

01:01:08.665 --> 01:01:12.043
He's very nervous when he's playing music,

01:01:12.126 --> 01:01:16.339
and he's very annoyed when he's doing
anything other than playing music.

01:01:16.422 --> 01:01:17.674
[man 2] Take 120.

01:01:18.216 --> 01:01:20.385
♪ Plain to see ♪

01:01:20.468 --> 01:01:24.847
♪ He's only, he's only
Playing a game ♪

01:01:27.600 --> 01:01:30.144
[Thompson] The conflict between
Elvis and the Colonel,

01:01:30.228 --> 01:01:33.606
or the conflict between the two Elvises,
however you want to frame it,

01:01:33.690 --> 01:01:38.986
is so clear in his
deep pain over messing up the music…

01:01:39.070 --> 01:01:40.613
[man] You'll walk into this. I'm sorry.

01:01:40.697 --> 01:01:44.784
♪ He's only, he's only
Playing a game ♪

01:01:45.451 --> 01:01:47.328
-[Elvis] I missed it, man.
-[man 3] Keep rolling.

01:01:47.412 --> 01:01:49.288
[Thompson] …and his deep annoyance

01:01:49.372 --> 01:01:52.959
at being forced
into the indignity of more skits.

01:01:53.042 --> 01:01:54.085
[man 2] Five-oh-two.

01:01:55.795 --> 01:01:58.548
[Elvis] Uh, where is downstage?
Is it that way?

01:01:58.631 --> 01:01:59.924
[man 2] It's downward, it's here.

01:02:00.007 --> 01:02:02.135
Can you see this blue mark here?

01:02:02.218 --> 01:02:04.262
Maybe something along here.

01:02:04.345 --> 01:02:07.140
Fourteen years, and I don't know
upstage from downstage, man.

01:02:08.391 --> 01:02:12.019
[Thompson] The premise of the special
was just a dopey Colonel Parker special.

01:02:13.980 --> 01:02:18.693
The producers of the show were handed
a Colonel Parker-packaged thing

01:02:18.776 --> 01:02:20.611
that was just more of the public Elvis

01:02:20.695 --> 01:02:23.406
as people had known him
for the last seven years.

01:02:24.031 --> 01:02:25.575
During breaks in the action,

01:02:26.284 --> 01:02:29.746
the private Elvis would go back
and do what the private Elvis always did,

01:02:29.829 --> 01:02:31.664
which was play music with his friends.

01:02:31.748 --> 01:02:33.833
[Elvis] If we want to,
we can do something like…

01:02:33.916 --> 01:02:35.668
[bluesy guitar tune playing]

01:02:35.752 --> 01:02:39.088
[Elvis] ♪ We're going up, we're going up ♪

01:02:39.172 --> 01:02:43.342
♪ Down, down, up
Anyway you want to let it roll ♪

01:02:45.470 --> 01:02:48.848
♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah ♪

01:02:51.809 --> 01:02:57.190
♪ You got me doin' what you want to do
Baby, what do you wanna do ♪

01:02:58.775 --> 01:03:01.569
[Thompson] And when the producers
of the show walked in and saw that,

01:03:01.652 --> 01:03:06.783
they realized that what Colonel
was trying to make him do was trash.

01:03:06.866 --> 01:03:11.037
And what Elvis was doing
in his actual private life was gold.

01:03:11.120 --> 01:03:14.582
[man] It's a bit like
"Blue Moon of Kentucky," isn't it?

01:03:14.665 --> 01:03:17.543
-[strumming guitar]
-[Elvis] What do you say "blue moon"?

01:03:18.085 --> 01:03:19.504
[man laughing] Yeah.

01:03:19.587 --> 01:03:21.047
♪ I say blue moon ♪

01:03:21.130 --> 01:03:23.800
[all chattering]

01:03:25.593 --> 01:03:28.763
Every day after rehearsal, he'd jam.
Acoustically.

01:03:28.846 --> 01:03:30.723
Whoever happened to be hanging out.

01:03:31.390 --> 01:03:34.727
Forget all the production,
forget the original concept.

01:03:34.811 --> 01:03:38.815
This is what the public is screaming for
that never, ever got to see.

01:03:38.898 --> 01:03:40.900
[Elvis and friends laughing on recording]

01:03:40.983 --> 01:03:43.569
[Elvis] You know,
I was thinking last night about…

01:03:44.862 --> 01:03:46.823
[plucking guitar tunefully]

01:03:46.906 --> 01:03:48.950
…incorporating this segment

01:03:49.992 --> 01:03:52.286
with the medley, somewhere in there.

01:03:53.454 --> 01:03:55.957
[man 1] I've been thinking about
the same thing, Elvis.

01:03:56.040 --> 01:03:59.627
[man 2] But we have to have that other
excitement to be able to do this, you see.

01:03:59.710 --> 01:04:02.338
'Cause now you're relaxing.
You've done your bit, you know.

01:04:02.421 --> 01:04:05.258
I go to Colonel Parker, I say,
"I'm bringing cameras in there."

01:04:05.341 --> 01:04:06.926
And he said, "Over my dead body."

01:04:07.009 --> 01:04:13.432
[Elvis] ♪ Well, well
Lawdy, lawdy, lawdy Miss Clawdy ♪

01:04:13.516 --> 01:04:17.144
♪ Girl, you sure look good to me ♪

01:04:17.854 --> 01:04:21.148
After days of hounding him,
he finally turned to me out of frustration

01:04:21.232 --> 01:04:24.777
and said, "I'll make a deal with you.
I'll let you recreate it on stage,

01:04:26.237 --> 01:04:31.284
but I won't promise you any of it goes
into the show that NBC broadcasts."

01:04:32.326 --> 01:04:35.204
[Thompson] When you see him
play these old standards,

01:04:35.288 --> 01:04:40.001
and blues songs, and gospel songs,
and the songs Elvis loved to listen to,

01:04:40.084 --> 01:04:42.044
when you saw him playing those onstage,

01:04:42.128 --> 01:04:44.297
that was literally them recreating

01:04:44.380 --> 01:04:46.716
what was happening organically
in his dressing room

01:04:46.799 --> 01:04:48.175
when the cameras were off.

01:04:48.259 --> 01:04:49.427
And what you remember

01:04:49.510 --> 01:04:55.266
is the growling, stalking Elvis
returning to the stage to say,

01:04:55.349 --> 01:04:57.602
"Yeah, yeah, yeah,
Keith Richards and Mick Jagger,

01:04:58.311 --> 01:05:00.229
but I'm Elvis fucking Presley."

01:05:00.313 --> 01:05:02.315
[whimsical music playing]

01:05:03.858 --> 01:05:08.321
[announcer 1] The following program is
brought to you in living color on NBC.

01:05:10.239 --> 01:05:13.618
[announcer 2] Singer presents,
Elvis starring Elvis Presley

01:05:13.701 --> 01:05:15.411
in his first TV special.

01:05:15.494 --> 01:05:18.831
His first personal performance
on TV in nearly ten years.

01:05:18.915 --> 01:05:20.917
[tense music playing]

01:05:21.918 --> 01:05:24.253
[Love] He told us
that he was very nervous.

01:05:25.838 --> 01:05:27.840
If the people were gonna like him.

01:05:27.924 --> 01:05:31.594
We didn't know whether Elvis was gonna
come out of his dressing room at all.

01:05:33.012 --> 01:05:34.013
Welcome to NBC…

01:05:34.096 --> 01:05:38.059
[O'Brien] Well, obviously I work in this
completely different realm.

01:05:38.142 --> 01:05:39.518
[audience clapping in distance]

01:05:39.602 --> 01:05:41.854
[O'Brien] But I will tell you that

01:05:42.730 --> 01:05:44.690
if you're not afraid, you're in trouble.

01:05:45.900 --> 01:05:47.526
If you want it to be good,

01:05:48.235 --> 01:05:49.278
you're petrified.

01:05:53.407 --> 01:05:55.451
It's a very lonely feeling.

01:05:56.160 --> 01:05:57.286
The fear…

01:05:58.955 --> 01:06:00.122
of failure

01:06:00.748 --> 01:06:02.583
is such a great motivator.

01:06:02.667 --> 01:06:04.210
The fear of embarrassment.

01:06:05.670 --> 01:06:09.715
We all know what it's like to be
in front of people and it doesn't go well.

01:06:10.383 --> 01:06:12.009
And it's terrible.

01:06:12.093 --> 01:06:13.886
[tense music continues]

01:06:18.724 --> 01:06:20.810
[O'Brien] "People are here, young people."

01:06:21.310 --> 01:06:24.647
"I don't even know if they like my music.
They probably like the Beatles."

01:06:25.231 --> 01:06:28.359
"They like Janis Joplin or Jimi Hendrix."

01:06:28.901 --> 01:06:30.653
"No one's gonna care about me."

01:06:30.736 --> 01:06:33.030
But there's something about

01:06:33.114 --> 01:06:37.159
being up against it
that enables you to do it.

01:06:37.243 --> 01:06:39.245
[tense music rises]

01:06:46.377 --> 01:06:49.588
I call it anticipatory anxiety.

01:06:49.672 --> 01:06:51.173
I can remember

01:06:51.257 --> 01:06:54.677
beginning of the Born in the U.S.A. tour,
we're in Saint Paul,

01:06:54.760 --> 01:06:57.763
and I sat backstage and it was
ten minutes before we went on,

01:06:57.847 --> 01:06:59.765
and I hear the crowd roaring.

01:07:00.599 --> 01:07:02.309
Roaring like crazy.

01:07:02.393 --> 01:07:03.227
And I'm going,

01:07:04.103 --> 01:07:05.187
"Oh man."

01:07:06.355 --> 01:07:07.857
"What have I got myself into?"

01:07:07.940 --> 01:07:12.403
You are going onto a stage
that you are unfamiliar with.

01:07:12.486 --> 01:07:17.324
Uh, you are being produced and directed
by people you don't really know.

01:07:20.036 --> 01:07:22.121
At some point,
you reach the "fuck it" point.

01:07:22.204 --> 01:07:24.457
Like, "I got to go out there,

01:07:24.540 --> 01:07:26.292
no matter what happens, fuck it."

01:07:26.375 --> 01:07:28.919
He reached the "fuck it" point. [laughing]

01:07:29.003 --> 01:07:31.380
You know,
that's what's going through his head.

01:07:31.464 --> 01:07:32.965
You know. He found it.

01:07:33.049 --> 01:07:36.093
And he was just go… And he was going.

01:07:36.177 --> 01:07:40.556
He was going
where his destiny was leading him.

01:07:46.729 --> 01:07:49.231
[Robertson] I was living in Woodstock,
New York.

01:07:49.315 --> 01:07:52.777
The other guys in The Band,
we were all there, and Bob Dylan.

01:07:52.860 --> 01:07:57.406
And when we heard about this special
coming on TV of Elvis's,

01:07:57.990 --> 01:08:01.035
Bob and I said, "Let's check it out."

01:08:01.786 --> 01:08:03.704
"Let's see if the old boy's still got it."

01:08:03.788 --> 01:08:05.539
["(If You're Looking For) Trouble"
playing]

01:08:05.623 --> 01:08:07.041
♪ If you're looking for trouble ♪

01:08:08.542 --> 01:08:10.211
♪ You came to the right place ♪

01:08:11.337 --> 01:08:12.838
♪ If you're looking for trouble ♪

01:08:14.340 --> 01:08:16.050
♪ Just look right in my face ♪

01:08:17.218 --> 01:08:18.803
♪ I was born standing up ♪

01:08:20.137 --> 01:08:21.514
♪ And talking back ♪

01:08:22.139 --> 01:08:27.394
♪ My daddy was
A green-eyed mountain jack ♪

01:08:27.478 --> 01:08:29.855
♪ Because I'm evil ♪

01:08:31.732 --> 01:08:35.444
♪ My middle name is misery ♪

01:08:35.528 --> 01:08:38.280
♪ Whoa, whoa, whoa ♪

01:08:39.240 --> 01:08:42.201
♪ Well, I'm evil ♪

01:08:43.494 --> 01:08:47.623
♪ So don't you mess around with me ♪

01:08:50.126 --> 01:08:52.128
[muted guitar riff playing]

01:08:56.132 --> 01:08:59.343
I had a little tiny dining room
with a big TV.

01:08:59.426 --> 01:09:03.639
And my father was in the kitchen,
but he could see the television from…

01:09:03.722 --> 01:09:04.557
[laughs]

01:09:04.640 --> 01:09:06.684
…from his spot on the kitchen table.

01:09:06.767 --> 01:09:09.228
And I sat in front of the TV.

01:09:10.187 --> 01:09:12.690
That was the rebirthing of Elvis Presley.

01:09:12.773 --> 01:09:14.150
[song transitions to "Guitar Man"]

01:09:14.233 --> 01:09:16.527
♪ Well, I nearly 'bout
Starved to death down in Memphis ♪

01:09:16.610 --> 01:09:18.320
♪ I'd run out of money and luck ♪

01:09:18.404 --> 01:09:20.781
I was sitting at the top.
I wanted to see everything.

01:09:20.865 --> 01:09:24.034
♪ …overloaded poultry truck
I thumbed on down to Panama City ♪

01:09:24.118 --> 01:09:27.288
He came onstage, he was like, "Wow."

01:09:27.371 --> 01:09:29.665
♪ I got the same old story
At them all night piers ♪

01:09:29.748 --> 01:09:32.126
♪ There ain't no room
Around here for a guitar man ♪

01:09:32.751 --> 01:09:34.086
I never saw him perform.

01:09:34.670 --> 01:09:37.965
That was the first time I saw him perform,
and I went, "Whoa."

01:09:38.048 --> 01:09:40.718
"This is what it's about?" [laughing]

01:09:40.801 --> 01:09:42.720
♪ I showed 'em
What a band would sound like ♪

01:09:42.803 --> 01:09:45.181
♪ With a swingin' little guitar man
Show 'em, son ♪

01:09:47.641 --> 01:09:49.894
[Springsteen] I don't think
I understood how good he was

01:09:49.977 --> 01:09:51.312
just seeing him once or twice.

01:09:51.979 --> 01:09:57.526
It was a reintroduction not just to who
he had been, but to who he could be.

01:09:58.235 --> 01:10:02.448
♪ Just follow that crowd of people
You'll wind up out on his dance floor ♪

01:10:02.531 --> 01:10:04.700
♪ Diggin' the finest
Little five-piece group ♪

01:10:04.783 --> 01:10:06.577
♪ Up and down the Gulf of Mexico ♪

01:10:06.660 --> 01:10:08.787
♪ Guess who's leadin'
That five-piece band ♪

01:10:08.871 --> 01:10:11.540
♪ Wouldn't you know
It's that swingin' little guitar man ♪

01:10:12.458 --> 01:10:14.835
[Schilling] It gave Elvis an edge.

01:10:16.337 --> 01:10:17.504
He still had it.

01:10:20.883 --> 01:10:23.385
It was developed, it was stronger.

01:10:25.221 --> 01:10:27.514
Elvis took Elvis to the next level.
[chuckles]

01:10:29.141 --> 01:10:31.143
[strumming guitar]

01:10:34.063 --> 01:10:35.689
[audience applauding]

01:10:36.690 --> 01:10:40.611
-[women whooping]
-[man laughing] All right!

01:10:44.949 --> 01:10:47.201
[O'Brien] One of the things
that strikes me right away

01:10:47.284 --> 01:10:49.453
is it's the best he's looked
in a long time.

01:10:50.412 --> 01:10:51.538
He comes out…

01:10:53.415 --> 01:10:57.044
and… he's the best-looking guy
on the planet.

01:11:01.131 --> 01:11:04.051
He comes out
and he's wearing that leather suit,

01:11:04.134 --> 01:11:08.097
and he's got those cheekbones
that are off a Greek statue.

01:11:09.265 --> 01:11:10.266
Well, good night.

01:11:10.349 --> 01:11:12.309
[all laughing]

01:11:12.393 --> 01:11:14.645
-[man 1] Been a long show.
-[man 2] It's been a long show.

01:11:14.728 --> 01:11:18.357
[O'Brien] For many years now,
he hasn't been in front of people

01:11:18.899 --> 01:11:20.526
performing music.

01:11:20.609 --> 01:11:22.736
There's been all these layers
of separation.

01:11:23.320 --> 01:11:24.947
Let's see, what do I do now, folks?

01:11:25.698 --> 01:11:27.992
All the insecurities that he would have,

01:11:28.075 --> 01:11:31.245
he's holding himself up
for possible ridicule.

01:11:31.870 --> 01:11:36.166
This is supposed to be an informal section
of the show where we faint

01:11:36.250 --> 01:11:38.669
or do whatever we want to do.
Especially me.

01:11:38.752 --> 01:11:42.589
[O'Brien] Yes, the guy in
the crazy outfits, and the hip shaking,

01:11:42.673 --> 01:11:45.676
and the big hair, is very shy,

01:11:45.759 --> 01:11:47.886
very sensitive person.

01:11:47.970 --> 01:11:50.973
We don't have our full band here tonight,
but we'd like to…

01:11:51.849 --> 01:11:56.145
we'd like to give you an idea of how we…
How I started out about 14 years ago.

01:11:56.645 --> 01:11:57.646
Uh…

01:11:58.605 --> 01:12:00.774
And the sound that we had back then.

01:12:01.608 --> 01:12:04.987
And the guy over here on my left
is the guy that played guitar for me

01:12:05.070 --> 01:12:08.407
when I first started out in 1912.
Nineteen…

01:12:09.825 --> 01:12:12.369
[Thompson] The show
isn't just Elvis's return.

01:12:12.453 --> 01:12:15.873
I mean, the show is Elvis literally
getting the band back together.

01:12:16.457 --> 01:12:19.543
This is Scotty Moore, my guitar player.

01:12:20.544 --> 01:12:23.005
[Thompson] That's his band
when he was still a country singer.

01:12:23.088 --> 01:12:25.591
That's the band
when he was on the Louisiana Hayride.

01:12:25.674 --> 01:12:27.926
That's the band
when he was playing in the Opry.

01:12:28.010 --> 01:12:30.721
This is my drummer.
He's from Shreveport, Louisiana.

01:12:30.804 --> 01:12:34.016
-[whistle softly]
-Met him about ten years ago, DJ Fontana.

01:12:34.099 --> 01:12:36.101
[audience applauding]

01:12:37.019 --> 01:12:39.646
You were watching musicians
who love each other,

01:12:39.730 --> 01:12:43.108
who fell away from each other,
who have come back to each other

01:12:43.192 --> 01:12:45.069
to capture the magic one more time.

01:12:45.152 --> 01:12:48.739
The first thing that we recorded,
we had a guitar, a bass,

01:12:48.822 --> 01:12:50.783
and another guitar.

01:12:51.533 --> 01:12:52.743
And it went like this.

01:12:56.497 --> 01:12:58.499
♪ Well, that's all right, mama ♪

01:12:58.582 --> 01:13:01.043
♪ That's all right with you ♪

01:13:01.126 --> 01:13:04.797
♪That's all right, mama
Just any way you do ♪

01:13:04.880 --> 01:13:06.882
♪ That's all right ♪

01:13:06.965 --> 01:13:08.884
♪ That's all right ♪

01:13:08.967 --> 01:13:11.845
♪ That's all right, now, mama ♪

01:13:11.929 --> 01:13:15.265
♪ Any way you do ♪

01:13:15.349 --> 01:13:18.644
[O'Brien] When he's sitting
in those chairs

01:13:18.727 --> 01:13:24.191
with his guys, and there's an audience
right there and they're surrounding him,

01:13:24.274 --> 01:13:26.360
and he's in an intimate environment,

01:13:27.027 --> 01:13:29.279
you can see the way
he can connect with people.

01:13:29.363 --> 01:13:33.325
♪ I'm leaving town, baby
I'm leaving town for sure ♪

01:13:33.409 --> 01:13:36.912
♪ Well, then you won't be bothered
With me hanging around your door ♪

01:13:36.995 --> 01:13:38.872
♪ But that's all right ♪

01:13:38.956 --> 01:13:42.167
[Springsteen] He looked incredible.
He sounded incredible.

01:13:42.251 --> 01:13:47.047
I felt like, "Oh, my team. My team,
they came back and they're…"

01:13:47.131 --> 01:13:49.842
You know, "They're winning again."
You know?

01:13:49.925 --> 01:13:51.093
Here we go, baby.

01:13:51.176 --> 01:13:55.139
♪ Dee-dee-de-deedee
Diggy-diggity-deedee ♪

01:13:55.222 --> 01:13:58.434
♪ Diggy-diggity-deedee
Dee-dee-dee-deedee-dee ♪

01:13:58.517 --> 01:13:59.726
♪ That's all right ♪

01:14:00.394 --> 01:14:01.603
♪ That's all right ♪

01:14:02.187 --> 01:14:04.773
♪ That's all right, now, mama ♪

01:14:04.857 --> 01:14:07.568
♪ Any way you do ♪

01:14:07.651 --> 01:14:09.445
♪ Dah-dah-dada-dah ♪

01:14:09.528 --> 01:14:11.155
-[audience cheering]
-[Elvis] Whoo!

01:14:11.238 --> 01:14:14.992
[Springsteen] That's just a revelation.
You know, just a musical revelation.

01:14:15.075 --> 01:14:19.538
You saw the incredible
high level of his artistry.

01:14:19.621 --> 01:14:22.416
The singing, unbelievable,

01:14:22.499 --> 01:14:25.419
and you saw him really play the guitar,

01:14:25.502 --> 01:14:27.713
and heard him play the guitar
for the first time.

01:14:27.796 --> 01:14:29.590
He was a really good guitarist.

01:14:29.673 --> 01:14:30.883
Are we on television?

01:14:32.259 --> 01:14:33.093
Are we on television?

01:14:33.177 --> 01:14:35.471
[man] No, we're on
a train bound for Tulsa.

01:14:35.554 --> 01:14:37.681
[bluesy guitar playing]

01:14:37.764 --> 01:14:40.434
-[man 1] Whoo!
-[man 2] Aw, get on down.

01:14:40.517 --> 01:14:43.562
[O'Brien] The moment for me
in the '68 Comeback Special

01:14:43.645 --> 01:14:46.482
is Elvis does,
"Baby, What Do You Want Me To Do."

01:14:48.942 --> 01:14:51.904
It's kind of a warm-up song,
like a blues warm-up.

01:14:52.779 --> 01:14:55.157
He's got that badass guitar,

01:14:55.240 --> 01:14:58.452
and you can tell that this
is what he was born to do.

01:15:00.204 --> 01:15:01.121
Yeah, baby!

01:15:05.250 --> 01:15:06.210
[man] Yeah!

01:15:10.756 --> 01:15:13.467
Everything that got him there
is now coming back,

01:15:13.550 --> 01:15:16.929
and everything that's interfered with that
has melted away.

01:15:17.596 --> 01:15:18.430
All of it.

01:15:18.514 --> 01:15:19.765
[guitar flourish]

01:15:19.848 --> 01:15:21.475
[man] Yeah!

01:15:21.558 --> 01:15:25.145
♪ You got me peeping, you got me hiding ♪

01:15:25.229 --> 01:15:28.148
[O'Brien] And it must be
a very powerful moment for him.

01:15:28.232 --> 01:15:29.816
He's coming back to life.

01:15:32.152 --> 01:15:34.154
And I think probably realizing

01:15:34.238 --> 01:15:36.114
"I'm Elvis fucking Presley."

01:15:36.198 --> 01:15:41.119
♪ You got me doing what you want me
Baby, what do you want me to do ♪

01:15:41.203 --> 01:15:43.413
There's something wrong with my lip, man.

01:15:43.497 --> 01:15:46.500
You know. No, wait a minute.
There's something wrong with my lip.

01:15:47.209 --> 01:15:48.794
[laughing]

01:15:48.877 --> 01:15:50.295
[chuckles]

01:15:50.379 --> 01:15:52.256
-[man] Well…
-You remember that, don't you?

01:15:52.339 --> 01:15:54.341
[all laughing]

01:15:55.050 --> 01:15:57.302
[audience applauding]

01:16:02.099 --> 01:16:04.851
I got news for you, baby.
I did 29 pictures like that.

01:16:04.935 --> 01:16:06.937
[all laughing]

01:16:08.564 --> 01:16:10.315
[Fontana] Hey, Elvis. The finger.

01:16:11.441 --> 01:16:12.276
The little finger.

01:16:12.359 --> 01:16:14.695
-That's all I could move in Florida.
-[Fontana] That's right.

01:16:14.778 --> 01:16:17.948
Yeah, the police filmed a show
one time in Florida because

01:16:18.740 --> 01:16:21.702
the PTA, the YMCA, or somebody,
they thought I was…

01:16:22.286 --> 01:16:23.120
[chuckles]

01:16:23.787 --> 01:16:26.081
-…something. And…
-[all laughing]

01:16:26.707 --> 01:16:28.917
They said, "Man, he's gotta be crazy."

01:16:29.001 --> 01:16:31.253
So, they…

01:16:31.920 --> 01:16:34.256
The police came out
and they filmed the show.

01:16:34.339 --> 01:16:36.592
So I couldn't move, I had to stand still.

01:16:37.092 --> 01:16:39.386
The only thing I could move
was my little finger.

01:16:39.886 --> 01:16:42.306
-♪ You ain't nothin' but a hound dog ♪
-[all laughing]

01:16:42.389 --> 01:16:43.890
♪ Cryin' all the time ♪

01:16:43.974 --> 01:16:45.684
You know, for the whole show.

01:16:46.310 --> 01:16:50.063
It's the most real thing anyone
had ever seen Elvis Presley do.

01:16:50.147 --> 01:16:52.232
It might be the first time

01:16:52.316 --> 01:16:55.110
that anyone had ever actually seen

01:16:55.193 --> 01:16:58.196
the actual human being
Elvis Aaron Presley,

01:16:58.280 --> 01:17:00.282
child of Tupelo in Memphis.

01:17:00.365 --> 01:17:04.536
So I told him, I said, "Well, look, man,
you can do anything you want to do."

01:17:04.620 --> 01:17:06.663
-[scoffs]
-[all laughing]

01:17:06.747 --> 01:17:08.665
"You can do anything
you want to do, baby."

01:17:09.666 --> 01:17:10.542
I said…

01:17:11.543 --> 01:17:14.463
♪ Well, that's one for the money
Two for the show ♪

01:17:14.546 --> 01:17:16.923
♪ Three to get ready, now go, cat, go ♪

01:17:17.007 --> 01:17:20.636
♪ But don't you
Step on my blue suede shoes ♪

01:17:22.054 --> 01:17:24.640
♪ You can do anything
But lay off of my blue suede shoes ♪

01:17:24.723 --> 01:17:25.932
[man] Oh, get it on!

01:17:27.267 --> 01:17:30.187
♪ Well, you can knock me down
Step in my face ♪

01:17:30.270 --> 01:17:32.814
♪ Slander my name all over the place ♪

01:17:32.898 --> 01:17:35.400
♪ Do anything that you want to do ♪

01:17:35.484 --> 01:17:37.778
♪ But uh-uh, honey, lay off of my shoes ♪

01:17:37.861 --> 01:17:41.281
♪ Don't step on my blue suede shoes ♪

01:17:42.699 --> 01:17:46.286
♪ Well, you can do anything
But lay off of my blue suede shoes ♪

01:17:48.080 --> 01:17:50.791
♪ You can burn my house, steal my car ♪

01:17:50.874 --> 01:17:51.917
♪ Drink my liquor… ♪

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:53.168
Oh my God.

01:17:54.211 --> 01:17:56.254
It's like… He was like a tiger.

01:17:56.338 --> 01:17:58.840
♪ Honey, lay off of my shoes and don't… ♪

01:17:59.966 --> 01:18:04.262
He was showing off
and doing his thing, and sexy,

01:18:04.346 --> 01:18:06.807
and it was like reincarnation.

01:18:06.890 --> 01:18:08.308
♪ Watch out, baby, watch out ♪

01:18:08.392 --> 01:18:10.394
[raucous guitar solo playing]

01:18:16.233 --> 01:18:17.484
"I'm married to him?"

01:18:18.151 --> 01:18:20.112
"Wow. Where have I been?"

01:18:27.953 --> 01:18:31.081
Oh my goodness. He was gorgeous.

01:18:31.164 --> 01:18:34.710
His hair was so shiny,
and the lights hit it.

01:18:34.793 --> 01:18:36.878
He was glowing like…

01:18:36.962 --> 01:18:40.924
I don't know what God looks like,
but you would say this guy was godlike.

01:18:41.007 --> 01:18:42.426
Ah!

01:18:43.593 --> 01:18:44.720
Ah, ah!

01:18:44.803 --> 01:18:46.304
Keep it going. That's right.

01:18:47.139 --> 01:18:49.182
[Tompkins] It was electric in there.

01:18:49.266 --> 01:18:51.101
It was breathtaking.

01:18:51.184 --> 01:18:54.980
♪ Well, you can do anything
But lay off of my blue suede shoes ♪

01:18:56.440 --> 01:18:59.067
-Ah!
-[music ends with flourish]

01:18:59.151 --> 01:19:00.736
[audience cheering loudly]

01:19:02.279 --> 01:19:06.658
[Priscilla] I remember a couple of girls,
they were going nuts over him.

